1
00:00:17,280 --> 00:00:20,960
JEREMY:
Tonight, James gets lost
in a Lamborghini.

2
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:24,120
Richard drives over a bridge
in a Ferrari.

3
00:00:24,160 --> 00:00:26,760
And I wear a small hat
in an Aston Martin.

4
00:00:31,760 --> 00:00:35,320
[APPLAUSE AND CHEERING]

5
00:00:35,360 --> 00:00:37,920
JEREMY: Hello! Thank you!

6
00:00:37,960 --> 00:00:40,560
Thank you very much,
thank you.

7
00:00:40,600 --> 00:00:43,320
We're back! We're back.

8
00:00:43,360 --> 00:00:47,920
And while we were
off air, the three
of us had a bit of an argument

9
00:00:47,960 --> 00:00:52,520
about what would be the best
car to take on
a Grand Tour of Europe.

10
00:00:52,560 --> 00:00:57,480
I reckon - and I'm right -
it's the Aston
Martin DBS Volante.

11
00:00:57,520 --> 00:01:01,960
Richard says, no, it isn't,
it's the Ferrari California,

12
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:04,880
and James -
who's a bit weird -

13
00:01:04,920 --> 00:01:07,520
says it's
the Lamborghini Gallardo.

14
00:01:07,560 --> 00:01:10,720
The new one,
with
the 560-horsepower engine.

15
00:01:10,760 --> 00:01:12,720
- Well, it is.
- No, it isn't!

16
00:01:12,760 --> 00:01:17,280
What that is is a two-seater,
mid-engine,
560-horsepower supercar.

17
00:01:17,320 --> 00:01:18,840
What you want for a Grand Tour

18
00:01:18,880 --> 00:01:20,960
is engine at the front,
nice comfy suspension,

19
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:22,760
four seats and a big boot
for all your luggage.

20
00:01:22,800 --> 00:01:26,160
- Which is why
you want the Aston.
- Well, yeah, it's the best.

21
00:01:26,200 --> 00:01:29,760
Apart from the fact that
the Ferrari costs £140,000,

22
00:01:29,800 --> 00:01:34,160
the Lambo
£150,000 and the Aston
is the best part of £170,000.

23
00:01:34,200 --> 00:01:36,600
- Yes.
- And it's
the slowest to 60mph.

24
00:01:36,640 --> 00:01:38,360
- Yes.
- And it's got
the smallest top speed.

25
00:01:38,400 --> 00:01:40,080
Yes. But...

26
00:01:40,120 --> 00:01:44,800
that's a V8,
that's a V10, that's a V12.
More is better.

27
00:01:44,840 --> 00:01:46,440
- [LAUGHTER]
- No!

28
00:01:46,480 --> 00:01:47,760
- It is.
- Isn't.

29
00:01:47,800 --> 00:01:48,680
- It is.
- It isn't.

30
00:01:48,720 --> 00:01:50,160
I'll hold my breath.

31
00:01:50,200 --> 00:01:53,760
- [LAUGHTER]
- He is now
holding his breath.

32
00:01:53,800 --> 00:01:56,720
Anyway, the producers said
that the only real
way to sort this out

33
00:01:56,760 --> 00:01:59,720
was to take these cars
on an actual Grand Tour.

34
00:01:59,760 --> 00:02:04,360
So we thought, "Yes! South
of France, or Italy,
or the Black Forest."

35
00:02:04,400 --> 00:02:07,520
But then they said no.
They said that we
had to take them...

36
00:02:07,560 --> 00:02:09,560
to Romania.

37
00:02:12,760 --> 00:02:16,560
JEREMY:
This is what springs to mind
when we think about Romania.

38
00:02:17,760 --> 00:02:19,880
Not that we do very often.

39
00:02:19,920 --> 00:02:25,040
We imagine it's full of oxes
and people throwing
stones at Gypsies.

40
00:02:30,400 --> 00:02:33,520
So you'd imagine
that turning up
in cars like this

41
00:02:33,560 --> 00:02:35,920
might look like showing off.

42
00:02:35,960 --> 00:02:37,960
We did, too.

43
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:42,600
Coming here in a car
that costs £168,000

44
00:02:42,640 --> 00:02:45,000
is a bit like
turning up in the Sudan

45
00:02:45,040 --> 00:02:47,160
in a suit made
entirely out of food.

46
00:02:48,840 --> 00:02:52,920
But then we arrived
in the Black Sea
town of Mamaia.

47
00:02:52,960 --> 00:02:56,760
And it wasn't really
what we were expecting.

48
00:02:57,520 --> 00:03:00,840
My God!

49
00:03:03,520 --> 00:03:05,280
Jag. Porsche.

50
00:03:05,320 --> 00:03:06,880
Ferrari. Ferrari.

51
00:03:06,920 --> 00:03:09,520
Audi R8 V10. Another Ferrari.

52
00:03:09,560 --> 00:03:13,040
If Simon Cowell came here,
they'd put him
on income support.

53
00:03:13,080 --> 00:03:14,240
Look at it!

54
00:03:14,280 --> 00:03:17,880
That's a 430. That's a 599.

55
00:03:17,920 --> 00:03:22,880
OK. We're not as conspicuous
as I first feared.

56
00:03:22,920 --> 00:03:26,640
- Have you ever
seen the like, Hammond?
- No, it's staggering!

57
00:03:26,680 --> 00:03:30,320
JEREMY:  And then, just when we
thought the car park couldn't
get any better...

58
00:03:30,360 --> 00:03:33,160
Oh, my God! That is, isn't it?

59
00:03:33,200 --> 00:03:35,960
- It is a Dacia Sandero.
- RICHARD: That is it.

60
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:37,640
JEREMY: I think this
is the 1.6.

61
00:03:37,680 --> 00:03:39,440
JAMES: I think it  isthe 1.6.

62
00:03:39,480 --> 00:03:41,960
I completely
forgot that this is
where the Sandero is from.

63
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:44,520
I've been
thinking about that car
for two years.

64
00:03:44,560 --> 00:03:47,320
RICHARD:
Sadly, before he could
think about it anymore,

65
00:03:47,360 --> 00:03:48,840
a challenge arrived.

66
00:03:49,960 --> 00:03:51,960
"You are here to
seek out a road

67
00:03:52,000 --> 00:03:54,280
"built by a former dictator.

68
00:03:54,320 --> 00:03:57,760
"Officially it's
called the Transf...
Transfi..."

69
00:03:57,800 --> 00:04:00,360
- That. Trans...
- Transfgs...

70
00:04:00,400 --> 00:04:06,160
"...Transfagarasan Highway.
Unofficially it's known as
Ceausescu's Folly.

71
00:04:06,200 --> 00:04:08,240
"People speak of it
in hushed whispers.

72
00:04:08,280 --> 00:04:11,800
"They say it's the best road
in the world."

73
00:04:11,840 --> 00:04:14,560
- So we're here
to look for it.
- We've got to find it.

74
00:04:17,120 --> 00:04:19,440
JEREMY:  We decided
to look in the mountains,

75
00:04:19,480 --> 00:04:21,840
which were 300 miles away.

76
00:04:21,880 --> 00:04:23,880
And on the journey, each of us

77
00:04:23,920 --> 00:04:26,760
would hope to
prove our car was best.

78
00:04:28,400 --> 00:04:32,920
Yes,
if you used facts and figures
when buying a car,

79
00:04:32,960 --> 00:04:36,320
you probably  wouldend up
with the Lamborghini
or the Ferrari,

80
00:04:36,360 --> 00:04:39,960
in the same way that if you
used facts and
figures to buy a house,

81
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:41,760
you'd end up in Dunfermline.

82
00:04:41,800 --> 00:04:43,840
Because you get a lot more
for your money.

83
00:04:46,240 --> 00:04:49,440
RICHARD: This is a whole new
type of car for Ferrari.

84
00:04:49,480 --> 00:04:52,520
This is the first
with a V8 engine
in the front.

85
00:04:52,560 --> 00:04:55,200
It's the first
direct injection engine
they've produced,

86
00:04:55,240 --> 00:04:58,160
it's the first Ferrari
with a metal folding roof.

87
00:04:58,200 --> 00:05:02,400
This is the first time Ferrari
have produced a car
with a DSG gearbox,

88
00:05:02,440 --> 00:05:05,200
which means you get absolutely
seamless gear changes.

89
00:05:08,320 --> 00:05:10,160
This isn't
a Ferrari for the track,

90
00:05:10,200 --> 00:05:14,000
it's for long journeys,
exactly like this one.

91
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:18,440
And now James
had the chance to explain

92
00:05:18,480 --> 00:05:23,920
why he'd brought a mid-engine
two-seater
supercar on a Grand Tour.

93
00:05:23,960 --> 00:05:26,160
By driving around
in a Lamborghini,

94
00:05:26,200 --> 00:05:28,960
you are actually
doing the world
a favour.

95
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:30,200
Because it's
a thing of beauty,

96
00:05:30,240 --> 00:05:33,480
other people can look at it
and they can enjoy it.

97
00:05:33,520 --> 00:05:35,480
It's like owning
one of Raphael's virgins

98
00:05:35,520 --> 00:05:37,960
and running around the streets
holding it above your head

99
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:41,160
instead of just
putting it on the wall.

100
00:05:41,200 --> 00:05:44,160
JEREMY:  So that we could talk
to each other on
our long journey,

101
00:05:44,200 --> 00:05:46,760
we decided to pull over
and connect our phones

102
00:05:46,800 --> 00:05:49,160
into the cars'
Bluetooth systems.

103
00:05:49,200 --> 00:05:53,600
In the Aston and
the Lamborghini,
this was very easy.

104
00:05:53,640 --> 00:05:56,440
Bluetooth, on.
Press enter to continue.

105
00:05:56,480 --> 00:05:58,560
Bluetooth on the phone.

106
00:05:58,600 --> 00:06:00,720
JEREMY:
However, in the Ferrari...

107
00:06:00,760 --> 00:06:04,040
ELECTRONIC VOICE:  Every new
phone must be paired
before it is used.

108
00:06:04,080 --> 00:06:06,080
- Yes, pairing my phone.
-  You may have
names and phone...

109
00:06:06,120 --> 00:06:08,160
Yes, yes, yes.

110
00:06:08,200 --> 00:06:11,440
...so that you can
press the phone's
button and say "Call Mary"

111
00:06:11,480 --> 00:06:13,480
to place a call to Mary.

112
00:06:13,520 --> 00:06:16,080
Pressing the VR button
while
the system is speaking...

113
00:06:16,120 --> 00:06:17,720
Please stop!

114
00:06:17,760 --> 00:06:20,760
Synchronising... Yes!

115
00:06:20,800 --> 00:06:23,960
I'm there! I'm connected!
I'm Bluetoothed!

116
00:06:24,000 --> 00:06:25,920
Bluetooth switched on.
Oh, joy.

117
00:06:25,960 --> 00:06:29,520
...Home,
work, mobile or pager. [BEEP]

118
00:06:29,560 --> 00:06:31,280
Work! I'm at work!

119
00:06:31,320 --> 00:06:35,840
- Name, please.
-Richard!
How does that help?!

120
00:06:35,880 --> 00:06:39,520
Please repeat the name
after the beep. [BEEP]

121
00:06:39,560 --> 00:06:43,240
JEREMY:  With our phones
connected - eventually - we
put our roofs up,

122
00:06:43,280 --> 00:06:46,520
which, without wishing
to boast, you can do on
the move in the Aston,

123
00:06:46,560 --> 00:06:50,600
and then we were ready for
a motorway blast to Bucharest.

124
00:06:57,560 --> 00:06:59,680
Oh! There's the V12!

125
00:07:01,520 --> 00:07:03,880
1, 2, 5, 0, 8...

126
00:07:03,920 --> 00:07:06,880
- What?!
-  ...0, 2, 0, 0, 0,

127
00:07:06,920 --> 00:07:10,920
- 0, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1...
- Clear!

128
00:07:16,560 --> 00:07:19,440
RICHARD:  Then we did
what we weren't
supposed to do.

129
00:07:19,480 --> 00:07:24,120
In 3, 2, 1, go!

130
00:07:26,120 --> 00:07:27,720
Oh, yeah,
this is what we mustn't do.

131
00:07:33,240 --> 00:07:35,080
A-ha-ha-ha!

132
00:07:36,800 --> 00:07:39,080
JEREMY: It just has the legs,
that Ferrari.

133
00:07:40,320 --> 00:07:42,440
Just, just, just.

134
00:07:42,480 --> 00:07:45,480
RICHARD:
Yeah, this might be a GT car,
but it's...

135
00:07:45,520 --> 00:07:48,280
It's not a slouch.

136
00:07:48,320 --> 00:07:51,480
JEREMY: Aston Martin has gone
to simply enormous lengths

137
00:07:51,520 --> 00:07:54,320
to make the DBS convertible
as light as possible.

138
00:07:54,360 --> 00:07:56,200
It has a carbon fibre bonnet,

139
00:07:56,240 --> 00:07:59,400
carbon fibre wings,
carbon fibre boot,

140
00:07:59,440 --> 00:08:01,640
carbon fibre door-pulls, even.

141
00:08:01,680 --> 00:08:06,440
They've even made the carpet
out of a specially
lightweight weave.

142
00:08:06,480 --> 00:08:08,280
And the results
speak for themselves.

143
00:08:08,320 --> 00:08:12,640
This is by far and away
the heaviest car of the three.

144
00:08:15,600 --> 00:08:17,760
JEREMY: Have you noticed
something, Hammond?

145
00:08:17,800 --> 00:08:19,640
- What?
- I don't see

146
00:08:19,680 --> 00:08:22,520
a black
Lamborghini anywhere near us.

147
00:08:22,560 --> 00:08:26,120
What, you mean the one
that is on paper
the fastest here?

148
00:08:27,520 --> 00:08:29,720
RICHARD:  James was merrily
tootling along,

149
00:08:29,760 --> 00:08:34,120
apparently under the illusion
he was presenting
his wine programme.

150
00:08:34,160 --> 00:08:36,080
Good place to stop
for a bag of grapes.

151
00:08:36,120 --> 00:08:41,040
There's three more people
holding up grapes, there's
a fourth...fifth, sixth.

152
00:08:41,080 --> 00:08:43,880
I think we're well covered
for grapes, there.

153
00:08:43,920 --> 00:08:47,880
JEREMY:
Meanwhile, Hammond's Ferrari
had decided all on its own

154
00:08:47,920 --> 00:08:49,720
to make a telephone call.

155
00:08:49,760 --> 00:08:53,160
- Selected.
Calling...Vernon Kay.
- What?! Vernon...?

156
00:08:53,200 --> 00:08:56,320
- Is this correct?
- Why are you
calling Vernon Kay?

157
00:08:56,360 --> 00:08:58,520
- [PHONE RINGS]
- Why are you doing that?

158
00:08:58,560 --> 00:09:00,960
-  Hello?
- Vernon?

159
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:05,080
-  Hi.
- Hello,
mate, it's Richard Hammond.

160
00:09:05,120 --> 00:09:09,280
JEREMY:  For miles,
our convoy ruled the road.
But then...

161
00:09:09,320 --> 00:09:11,040
Oh, my God! Look out!

162
00:09:13,160 --> 00:09:15,400
What's that?! Wha..?

163
00:09:15,440 --> 00:09:18,040
That's the Dacia Sandero.

164
00:09:18,080 --> 00:09:20,240
I'm going to see
if I can hold on
to the back of it.

165
00:09:20,280 --> 00:09:23,840
JAMES: The 1.2 16-valve -
that thing can shift!

166
00:09:23,880 --> 00:09:28,560
Come on!
Keep up with the Sandero!

167
00:09:28,600 --> 00:09:32,080
Hammond's Ferrari
might have got it,
but unfortunately...

168
00:09:32,120 --> 00:09:33,800
- [PHONE RINGS]
- Why are you doing that now?

169
00:09:33,840 --> 00:09:36,440
Why are you
calling Vernon Kay again?

170
00:09:36,480 --> 00:09:38,680
- Hi, Richard.
- Vernon!

171
00:09:38,720 --> 00:09:41,560
Er,
it's Richard Hammond...again.

172
00:09:41,600 --> 00:09:43,400
Er...I'm really sorry.

173
00:09:43,440 --> 00:09:47,240
No, it's fine.
I'm just in the studio,
everyone's stopped work.

174
00:09:47,280 --> 00:09:49,240
Good. Good.

175
00:09:49,280 --> 00:09:50,920
Um...

176
00:09:54,400 --> 00:09:57,160
JEREMY:  While refuelling
on the outskirts of Bucharest,

177
00:09:57,200 --> 00:09:59,520
James and Richard bought me
a present.

178
00:09:59,560 --> 00:10:01,000
- Great!
- What now?

179
00:10:01,040 --> 00:10:03,160
My life is complete,
that's what.

180
00:10:03,200 --> 00:10:04,960
Very big round here,
apparently.

181
00:10:05,000 --> 00:10:07,520
And then James thought of
a new game.

182
00:10:07,560 --> 00:10:10,440
Why don't we have
a sat nav challenge?

183
00:10:10,480 --> 00:10:13,880
Because mine is a German one
and will be superior.

184
00:10:13,920 --> 00:10:15,720
- It's Audi, isn't it?
- It is.

185
00:10:15,760 --> 00:10:18,120
Good idea. We can start here.

186
00:10:18,160 --> 00:10:21,640
Ready steady go,
set your sat nav
for the People's Palace.

187
00:10:21,680 --> 00:10:26,040
I know it exists. First to
get to the People's
Palace is the winner.

188
00:10:26,080 --> 00:10:27,520
- Are you ready?
- Yes.

189
00:10:27,560 --> 00:10:29,040
- Steady?
- Yes.

190
00:10:29,080 --> 00:10:30,720
Go!

191
00:10:30,760 --> 00:10:33,840
I should explain
before we start,
I have a Volvo system.

192
00:10:33,880 --> 00:10:39,200
Unanimously, everybody agrees
it's the worst sat
nav in the world.

193
00:10:39,240 --> 00:10:43,240
Rise! Rise!

194
00:10:43,280 --> 00:10:45,240
RICHARD:  Mercifully,
in the California,

195
00:10:45,280 --> 00:10:48,320
the sat nav system was
much better
than the Bluetooth.

196
00:10:48,360 --> 00:10:52,040
Nearby point of interest,
that's the first
order of business.

197
00:10:52,080 --> 00:10:55,960
Whereas in the Lambo,
James was
regretting his new game.

198
00:10:56,000 --> 00:11:01,000
Country.
I, J, K, L, M, N, O, P, Q...

199
00:11:01,040 --> 00:11:05,320
It goes from
Portugal to San...
How can it not have...?

200
00:11:05,360 --> 00:11:09,560
The Italians don't acknowledge
the existence of Romania.

201
00:11:09,600 --> 00:11:12,640
1-1-7. 1-1...

202
00:11:12,680 --> 00:11:16,320
No, no, no.
1 to 42, that is all.

203
00:11:16,360 --> 00:11:17,200
Right, I've got it.

204
00:11:18,720 --> 00:11:20,400
[RICHARD CACKLES]

205
00:11:20,440 --> 00:11:22,160
No! No, no!

206
00:11:23,360 --> 00:11:25,080
Er, People's Palace?

207
00:11:25,120 --> 00:11:27,800
People?

208
00:11:27,840 --> 00:11:30,640
Not the best
present I've ever had,
if I'm honest,

209
00:11:30,680 --> 00:11:33,160
but it's tactless
to just ignore them.

210
00:11:33,200 --> 00:11:35,160
- SAT NAV:
Please follow the road.
- Yes.

211
00:11:35,200 --> 00:11:40,280
I will gladly follow the road,
for...7.3kms.

212
00:11:40,320 --> 00:11:43,440
Technology and I are now
getting on absolutely fine.

213
00:11:43,480 --> 00:11:48,040
- Calling Stephen Accountant.
- No, no, no, don't do that.

214
00:11:48,080 --> 00:11:51,120
- Go to the roundabout here.
- Yep.

215
00:11:51,160 --> 00:11:52,240
And here...

216
00:11:52,280 --> 00:11:55,520
- Here in sub...
- No.

217
00:11:55,560 --> 00:11:59,600
One of the most irritating
things about the Volvo
system that Aston use,

218
00:11:59,640 --> 00:12:02,440
is that it tells
you where you've been.

219
00:12:02,480 --> 00:12:06,560
Which is only of
any use if you think
your wife's having an affair.

220
00:12:06,600 --> 00:12:08,560
James was now on the move,

221
00:12:08,600 --> 00:12:12,040
but obviously his
map had been drawn
by a distant relative.

222
00:12:12,080 --> 00:12:14,640
JAMES:
When he said roundabout,
did he mean roundabout?

223
00:12:14,680 --> 00:12:17,360
Or did he mean crossroads?

224
00:12:17,400 --> 00:12:21,040
Fortunately, the producers
had given me
a Romanian phrasebook.

225
00:12:21,080 --> 00:12:24,480
Unfortunately,
it was a bit confusing.

226
00:12:24,520 --> 00:12:26,080
[HE TALKS IN ROMANIAN]

227
00:12:35,640 --> 00:12:37,960
JEREMY:
Meanwhile, less than a mile
from the People's Palace,

228
00:12:38,000 --> 00:12:40,800
the sat nav race
was hotting up.

229
00:12:41,480 --> 00:12:43,560
Hammond! Get him!

230
00:12:43,600 --> 00:12:44,840
What's he doing here?

231
00:12:44,880 --> 00:12:46,040
Come on!

232
00:12:46,800 --> 00:12:48,400
[LAUGHS]

233
00:12:48,440 --> 00:12:52,000
RICHARD:
I'm winning by 1.5 metres.
I found it first.

234
00:12:52,040 --> 00:12:53,800
JEREMY: No, I found it
with my eyes.

235
00:12:53,840 --> 00:12:55,720
No, you didn't.
I found it first.

236
00:12:57,320 --> 00:12:59,080
[HE SPEAKS ROMANIAN]

237
00:13:04,480 --> 00:13:07,600
JEREMY:  Hammond and I,
meanwhile, were still racing.

238
00:13:07,640 --> 00:13:10,640
- This...
- Ha-ha-ha!

239
00:13:10,680 --> 00:13:14,880
But when we saw
the People's Palace,
we sort of stopped.

240
00:13:18,200 --> 00:13:21,000
Today it's the Romanian
parliament building.

241
00:13:21,040 --> 00:13:28,120
But it was once the private
house of notorious
dictator Nicolae Ceausescu.

242
00:13:28,160 --> 00:13:33,040
RICHARD: If that's his idea
of a house, what's his idea of
a road gonna be like?

243
00:13:33,080 --> 00:13:36,800
You know that is
the heaviest building
in the world?

244
00:13:36,840 --> 00:13:38,360
That's what you'd build,
isn't it?

245
00:13:38,400 --> 00:13:42,160
It is. A million cubic metres
of marble in there.

246
00:13:42,200 --> 00:13:44,680
- Ceausescu was a mental,
wasn't he?
- Complete mental.

247
00:13:44,720 --> 00:13:46,760
And an unpleasant mental.

248
00:13:46,800 --> 00:13:50,480
He had people go ahead
of him and paint the leaves
green wherever he went.

249
00:13:50,520 --> 00:13:54,520
JEREMY: As we waited,
James had become really lost.

250
00:14:00,800 --> 00:14:03,280
It  isthe Arc de Triomphe.
It's...

251
00:14:03,320 --> 00:14:05,520
priorite a droite.

252
00:14:08,240 --> 00:14:09,520
That's it.

253
00:14:10,960 --> 00:14:12,920
JEREMY:  While we waited,
we were informed

254
00:14:12,960 --> 00:14:16,840
we might get a visit
from a local dignitary.

255
00:14:16,880 --> 00:14:21,400
The Secretary General
of the Chamber of Deputies.

256
00:14:21,440 --> 00:14:23,640
Jeremy, you are familiar with
the local customs, aren't you?

257
00:14:23,680 --> 00:14:25,520
- What?
- Penis out.

258
00:14:25,560 --> 00:14:28,040
When she stands
to shake hands,
you just plop it in.

259
00:14:28,080 --> 00:14:31,640
And that's what you do.
That's how it works.

260
00:14:31,680 --> 00:14:33,120
- Hello, sir.
- Hello.

261
00:14:34,560 --> 00:14:36,520
[SPEAKS IN ROMANIAN]

262
00:14:42,800 --> 00:14:46,600
Do you remember in 2009
they used to make that?
What was it called?

263
00:14:46,640 --> 00:14:49,520
- It was a Lam...Lam...
- Lamborghini.

264
00:14:49,560 --> 00:14:50,960
Behold the People's Palace.

265
00:14:51,000 --> 00:14:53,080
- James, you lost that one.
- Quite badly.

266
00:14:56,880 --> 00:15:00,480
JEREMY:  While waiting
for James, the local dignitary
had given us permission

267
00:15:00,520 --> 00:15:04,720
to drive in the network
of tunnels underneath
the government building.

268
00:15:06,440 --> 00:15:10,080
This, we feel, is not
something that would be
allowed in Britain.

269
00:15:16,000 --> 00:15:17,840
Start the music!

270
00:15:19,360 --> 00:15:20,760
Wa-ha!

271
00:15:27,000 --> 00:15:28,080
Oh, yeah!

272
00:15:29,440 --> 00:15:31,720
Jeez, there's a corner there!

273
00:15:33,480 --> 00:15:34,960
[ENGINES ROAR]

274
00:15:40,400 --> 00:15:42,640
Dust. Dust!

275
00:15:42,680 --> 00:15:45,360
Can't see a thing!

276
00:15:45,400 --> 00:15:49,040
We then decided to bring
a bit of science to the party.

277
00:15:50,080 --> 00:15:51,760
[ENGINE REVS]

278
00:15:53,000 --> 00:15:54,680
That is a decibel-o-meter

279
00:15:54,720 --> 00:15:58,600
and I'm going to see how loud
the Ferrari is.

280
00:15:58,640 --> 00:15:59,640
- Ready?
- Mm-hm.

281
00:15:59,680 --> 00:16:01,800
Not too bad, 70...82.

282
00:16:04,560 --> 00:16:05,880
Yeow.

283
00:16:14,400 --> 00:16:15,680
- 89?
- 89.

284
00:16:15,720 --> 00:16:16,840
I saw an 89 average.

285
00:16:16,880 --> 00:16:18,480
- I saw 89.
- 89, yeah.

286
00:16:18,520 --> 00:16:20,680
- What a lot of dust! Jeez!
- It's quite dusty down there.

287
00:16:20,720 --> 00:16:22,640
This is our best game yet.

288
00:16:22,680 --> 00:16:25,560
All you need to play
this game, in case you're
interested at home,

289
00:16:25,600 --> 00:16:27,000
is a People's Palace,

290
00:16:27,040 --> 00:16:28,640
- with a tunnel underneath it.
- Yeah.

291
00:16:28,680 --> 00:16:32,080
Three supercars
and a cheap app
and you're there!

292
00:16:35,160 --> 00:16:38,520
It turned out that
all three cars
were equally loud.

293
00:16:41,200 --> 00:16:46,360
So, we abandoned the science
and went to the pub...

294
00:16:46,400 --> 00:16:50,520
...where we were
just in time to catch
the local version ofTop Gear.

295
00:16:50,560 --> 00:16:52,520
[SPEAKS IN ROMANIAN]

296
00:16:54,960 --> 00:16:56,920
I just wish that girl
would get out the way,

297
00:16:56,960 --> 00:17:00,240
so we could see the car more!

298
00:17:00,280 --> 00:17:02,880
I bet that would sound good
in the tunnels.

299
00:17:02,920 --> 00:17:05,480
RICHARD:
What a magnificent thing.

300
00:17:10,120 --> 00:17:13,120
[CHEERING AND APPLAUSE]

301
00:17:13,160 --> 00:17:15,680
We'll pick that, er,
we'll pick that up later on.

302
00:17:16,840 --> 00:17:20,920
But now it is
time to do the news.

303
00:17:20,960 --> 00:17:23,120
And we begin with a story
from Australia, in fact.

304
00:17:23,160 --> 00:17:27,320
Er, Australian authorities
are really going to get tough

305
00:17:27,360 --> 00:17:30,960
on boozed-up fans
at the Bathurst Motor Race.

306
00:17:31,000 --> 00:17:33,080
Well, I say motor race,
it's actually a fight

307
00:17:33,120 --> 00:17:37,760
between rival gangs of
Ford supporters
and GM supporters.

308
00:17:37,800 --> 00:17:40,040
The way they've
cracked this is,
they say

309
00:17:40,080 --> 00:17:46,240
each fan is going to be
limited to just 24 cans of
lager each per day.

310
00:17:46,280 --> 00:17:49,320
- Just 24?
- 24 a day, no more than that.

311
00:17:49,360 --> 00:17:53,520
Australians, don't think you
can get round this by
switching to wine,

312
00:17:53,560 --> 00:17:55,200
because that's
limited as well...

313
00:17:55,240 --> 00:17:58,160
to four litres a day.

314
00:17:58,200 --> 00:18:00,480
Do you know what they're doing
to get round it?

315
00:18:00,520 --> 00:18:02,600
- What, Australians?
- Yeah.

316
00:18:02,640 --> 00:18:07,080
Australians are going there
two weeks before the race
and burying beer.

317
00:18:07,120 --> 00:18:09,000
We have an Australian guest
on later.

318
00:18:09,040 --> 00:18:10,120
I'm going to talk
to him about this.

319
00:18:10,160 --> 00:18:11,760
- I'm fascinated.
- Yes. Now...

320
00:18:11,800 --> 00:18:13,240
- We must move on.
- We must.

321
00:18:13,280 --> 00:18:16,320
McLaren have a announced
a new supercar, here it is.

322
00:18:16,360 --> 00:18:19,120
It's called the MP4-12C.

323
00:18:19,160 --> 00:18:21,920
JEREMY: Mmmm.
That'll sound good
with adenoids.

324
00:18:21,960 --> 00:18:26,120
"Wanna come for a ride
in my MP4 dash 12C?"

325
00:18:26,160 --> 00:18:27,880
No, I don't, it sounds like
a telephone.

326
00:18:27,920 --> 00:18:30,560
However, interesting thing
about this car particularly

327
00:18:30,600 --> 00:18:33,920
is the previous
McLaren supercars,
the F1 and the Merc SLR,

328
00:18:33,960 --> 00:18:36,480
- were very, very expensive.
- Mmm.

329
00:18:36,520 --> 00:18:38,960
This - £170,000.

330
00:18:39,000 --> 00:18:40,720
- Oh, cheap.
- Oh, that's all right, then.

331
00:18:40,760 --> 00:18:43,440
- As I said that I realised...
- I know what you mean,
it's cheap-er.

332
00:18:43,480 --> 00:18:46,400
- It's kind of the same...
- Half the price of the SLR.

333
00:18:46,440 --> 00:18:48,440
This is the first time they've
put their own engine into it,

334
00:18:48,480 --> 00:18:52,200
3.8 litre twin turbo V8,
so there's a lot of exciting
things about it.

335
00:18:52,240 --> 00:18:54,520
I hope that works.
McLaren have
had a rotten week.

336
00:18:54,560 --> 00:18:58,640
All their vehicles have been
recalled, cos they've been
amputating limbs.

337
00:18:58,680 --> 00:19:00,880
No, that's not...no, yeah.

338
00:19:00,920 --> 00:19:03,280
It's not the vehicles, mate,

339
00:19:03,320 --> 00:19:05,920
it's the prams,
the pushchairs,
Maclaren buggies.

340
00:19:05,960 --> 00:19:09,880
Oh! I thought Rowan Atkinson
had had his arm cut
off by his car.

341
00:19:09,920 --> 00:19:11,520
- No...
- It's Maclaren prams?

342
00:19:11,560 --> 00:19:13,760
- Yes,
the buggies, the pushchairs.
- Oh, God!

343
00:19:13,800 --> 00:19:15,240
Interesting thing
about this story is

344
00:19:15,280 --> 00:19:19,080
it's come about because of
12 cases in the States

345
00:19:19,120 --> 00:19:21,280
- of children
having fingers amputated.
- Mm.

346
00:19:21,320 --> 00:19:24,440
As a result, they've recalled
all the pushchairs.

347
00:19:24,480 --> 00:19:26,200
But
the pushchairs are the same
all over the world

348
00:19:26,240 --> 00:19:28,800
and it's only in the States
that they're recalling them.

349
00:19:28,840 --> 00:19:30,360
Not over here, for instance.

350
00:19:30,400 --> 00:19:32,280
There's a very good reason
for that though.

351
00:19:32,320 --> 00:19:37,680
British parents are more...
What's the word
I'm looking for?

352
00:19:37,720 --> 00:19:39,200
- Intelligent.
- Yes!

353
00:19:40,520 --> 00:19:42,080
- Cos how could you...?
- Hey!

354
00:19:42,120 --> 00:19:43,920
[US ACCENT] I can't shut
this buggy down,

355
00:19:43,960 --> 00:19:46,760
there's these pink
things in the way.

356
00:19:46,800 --> 00:19:51,600
[US ACCENT] I've
got the kid screaming
his head off! Shut up, Junior!

357
00:19:51,640 --> 00:19:53,560
- That's got it!
- Stop yelling.

358
00:19:53,600 --> 00:19:55,200
It's...there you go.

359
00:19:55,240 --> 00:19:58,200
Now, do you want to combine
your love of camping,

360
00:19:58,240 --> 00:20:01,040
with your love of buying
the wrong Porsche?

361
00:20:02,120 --> 00:20:03,920
No,
because I have good news, OK?

362
00:20:03,960 --> 00:20:09,080
Because you can now buy,
um, well, it's a new type
of Boxster, OK?

363
00:20:09,120 --> 00:20:12,240
With a tent on the top of it.
Here it is.

364
00:20:12,280 --> 00:20:15,600
Look at that roof!
It looks like a tramp's hat.

365
00:20:15,640 --> 00:20:20,840
It's called the Boxster Spyder
and it's a super
lightweight version.

366
00:20:20,880 --> 00:20:26,720
It only weighs
1,250 kilos, top speed
166mph, 0-60 in 4.8 seconds.

367
00:20:26,760 --> 00:20:29,040
And it's that fast because
it's got a very
clever gearbox.

368
00:20:29,080 --> 00:20:31,880
It's called a...it's...
Well, it's...

369
00:20:31,920 --> 00:20:33,320
- Is it German?
- It's a German name.

370
00:20:33,360 --> 00:20:34,680
- Oh!
- And it's complicated.

371
00:20:34,720 --> 00:20:39,400
Let me just spell this out -
it's a D-O-P-P-E-L

372
00:20:39,440 --> 00:20:43,240
K-U-P-P-L

373
00:20:43,280 --> 00:20:45,400
U-N-G

374
00:20:45,440 --> 00:20:48,920
S-G-E

375
00:20:49,280 --> 00:20:51,560
T...R...

376
00:20:53,240 --> 00:20:54,520
...I-E...

377
00:20:55,320 --> 00:20:56,560
...B...

378
00:20:57,160 --> 00:20:58,640
...E.

379
00:20:58,680 --> 00:20:59,800
That's what it is...I...

380
00:20:59,840 --> 00:21:02,840
Can we? Get it on the screen.

381
00:21:02,880 --> 00:21:04,480
Are there any Germans here?

382
00:21:04,520 --> 00:21:06,200
- That's a long word!
- That is a...

383
00:21:06,240 --> 00:21:07,960
Do you know what that means?
You speak German.

384
00:21:08,000 --> 00:21:11,080
- I do.
- What's the only
German you can say?

385
00:21:11,120 --> 00:21:13,440
Aber ja,
naturlich Hans ist nass,
er steht unter dem Wasserfall.

386
00:21:13,480 --> 00:21:15,320
What's that mean?

387
00:21:15,360 --> 00:21:17,440
Naturally Hans is wet,
he's standing
under a waterfall.

388
00:21:17,480 --> 00:21:18,960
[LAUGHTER]

389
00:21:19,000 --> 00:21:21,080
- OK.
- I use it all the time.

390
00:21:21,120 --> 00:21:24,440
That's kind of
a one-shot deal,
isn't it?

391
00:21:24,480 --> 00:21:29,280
Er, anyway,
if you want the wrong car,
which has no door handles,

392
00:21:29,320 --> 00:21:33,280
and no air conditioning and
no radio and has a tent
on the top of it,

393
00:21:33,320 --> 00:21:35,840
- then there you are,
the Boxster...
- Spyder.

394
00:21:35,880 --> 00:21:39,280
It's not got all those things
to keep it light,
cos it's still 44 grand.

395
00:21:39,320 --> 00:21:41,640
£44,000, you don't even get
door handles.

396
00:21:43,080 --> 00:21:44,920
We've been sent this.

397
00:21:44,960 --> 00:21:50,600
It's an eco-friendly,
portable, disposable,
cardboard lavatory,

398
00:21:50,640 --> 00:21:52,440
for use by
the side of the road.

399
00:21:52,480 --> 00:21:54,880
The idea is
you're driving along,
you get caught a bit short,

400
00:21:54,920 --> 00:21:58,320
can't find the nearest khazi,
you pop this out, erect it

401
00:21:58,360 --> 00:21:59,720
- and do what you have to do.
- Are you about to tell us

402
00:21:59,760 --> 00:22:01,040
- you have been caught short?
- No.

403
00:22:01,080 --> 00:22:02,960
- Cos I don't
think you should.
- No.

404
00:22:03,000 --> 00:22:06,000
I was going to say, we should
give this a fair
test on  Top Gear

405
00:22:06,040 --> 00:22:09,960
by giving it to the world's
most practical man,
which is...Clarkson.

406
00:22:11,800 --> 00:22:13,960
- What,
you want me to build it?
- I do.

407
00:22:14,000 --> 00:22:16,640
Oh, God,
I hate this sort of thing.

408
00:22:16,680 --> 00:22:18,600
Where's the instructions?

409
00:22:18,640 --> 00:22:21,320
Have you ever noticed,
watching him do
anything practical,

410
00:22:21,360 --> 00:22:23,480
it's like
watching an orang-utan?

411
00:22:23,520 --> 00:22:25,680
It is! Look at his face.

412
00:22:25,720 --> 00:22:27,320
Honestly, look at his face,
it goes all...

413
00:22:27,360 --> 00:22:29,200
- It's very long.
- He's happy, but confused.

414
00:22:29,240 --> 00:22:30,760
[LAUGHTER]

415
00:22:30,800 --> 00:22:32,960
They actually put a picture
of Jeremy on the bag, look,

416
00:22:33,000 --> 00:22:34,960
showing you how
to assemble it.

417
00:22:35,000 --> 00:22:37,320
These instructions,
look at these!

418
00:22:37,360 --> 00:22:42,400
They bear no relation,
as always, to the thing
they're supplied with.

419
00:22:42,440 --> 00:22:43,760
See, he's doing the ape thing.

420
00:22:43,800 --> 00:22:46,280
And bear in mind,
you have to erect this...

421
00:22:46,320 --> 00:22:48,320
while basically desperate
for a number two, with...

422
00:22:48,360 --> 00:22:50,480
- I was going to say...
- ...with lorries going by.

423
00:22:50,520 --> 00:22:53,640
Could you erect
this while you were
touching cloth? You can?

424
00:22:53,680 --> 00:22:55,240
[LAUGHTER]

425
00:22:55,280 --> 00:22:57,120
See if you can
get that erected.

426
00:22:57,160 --> 00:22:59,200
I'm prepared to bet
that question has
never been asked

427
00:22:59,240 --> 00:23:03,200
- on any other car show ever.
- [LAUGHTER]

428
00:23:03,240 --> 00:23:05,480
- RICHARD: She's good.
- How've you done that?

429
00:23:05,520 --> 00:23:07,320
She's bloody done it, look.

430
00:23:07,360 --> 00:23:09,160
That was it?

431
00:23:09,200 --> 00:23:10,440
How did you do that?

432
00:23:10,480 --> 00:23:12,560
Look, she's made a lavatory.

433
00:23:12,600 --> 00:23:14,000
[CHEERING]

434
00:23:16,280 --> 00:23:17,360
You did what?

435
00:23:17,400 --> 00:23:19,360
I'm female.

436
00:23:19,400 --> 00:23:21,480
You're a... She's a female.

437
00:23:24,560 --> 00:23:26,920
So, you just put
that up at the side
of the road and then...

438
00:23:26,960 --> 00:23:29,560
There's no need
to demonstrate!

439
00:23:35,120 --> 00:23:37,680
How did you think
that was going to go?

440
00:23:37,720 --> 00:23:40,120
How did you think
that was going to work?

441
00:23:40,160 --> 00:23:43,200
You great, dopey ape.

442
00:23:43,240 --> 00:23:46,600
Do you know what, honestly?
I'd rather just crap myself.

443
00:23:46,640 --> 00:23:48,640
I think I just did! Yeah.

444
00:23:51,120 --> 00:23:52,360
Can we move on?

445
00:23:52,400 --> 00:23:54,240
I'm not the world's
most unpractical man.

446
00:23:54,280 --> 00:23:57,200
- You are.
- I am, actually.
You're right.

447
00:23:57,240 --> 00:24:00,560
- Anyway, we've got to get on.
- Yes,
anyway, we've had a letter.

448
00:24:00,600 --> 00:24:03,560
It's literally
from some bankers
and it says,

449
00:24:03,600 --> 00:24:07,920
"Dear  Top Gear,
this time last year,
we didn't have any money,

450
00:24:07,960 --> 00:24:09,680
"but the Government
has given us some now.

451
00:24:09,720 --> 00:24:13,040
"However, we don't want
the public to know that
we're loaded again,

452
00:24:13,080 --> 00:24:16,760
"so we need really fast,
expensive cars that
are quite discreet.

453
00:24:16,800 --> 00:24:19,840
"Can you help?
Yours sincerely,
some bankers."

454
00:24:19,880 --> 00:24:23,680
Well, as it happens,
yes, we can help.

455
00:24:27,560 --> 00:24:30,480
JAMES:
And we begin with something
from BMW.

456
00:24:35,800 --> 00:24:39,280
This here is the BMW 760Li.

457
00:24:39,320 --> 00:24:43,320
Or to give it
it's other name -
the BMW Move Over Poor Person.

458
00:24:43,360 --> 00:24:45,880
Because this is the biggest,
most expensive

459
00:24:45,920 --> 00:24:49,000
and most
powerful car BMW makes.

460
00:24:52,480 --> 00:24:56,480
It has a six-litre V12,
which sounds like plenty.

461
00:24:56,520 --> 00:25:00,440
But, obviously,
someone at BMW thought, "No".

462
00:25:00,480 --> 00:25:05,040
So, for a bit of extra
"schnell", this car has got
two turbo chargers.

463
00:25:06,680 --> 00:25:10,360
The result is 544bhp.

464
00:25:10,400 --> 00:25:12,640
And the power station
under the bonnet is connected

465
00:25:12,680 --> 00:25:17,200
to a brand-new
eight-speed gearbox.

466
00:25:17,240 --> 00:25:20,360
Put all that lot together
and even someone
as laid back as me

467
00:25:20,400 --> 00:25:24,040
can quite easily...
look, get a bit of a lick on.

468
00:25:28,120 --> 00:25:32,240
It'll batter most 911s
in a sprint to 60,

469
00:25:32,280 --> 00:25:37,040
and de-limited,
it would hit 188mph.

470
00:25:37,080 --> 00:25:40,800
But those numbers only tell
half the story.

471
00:25:43,040 --> 00:25:45,200
This is
a bizarre kind of fast.

472
00:25:45,240 --> 00:25:48,400
It's quiet and
relaxed and smooth.

473
00:25:48,440 --> 00:25:52,080
It's like swimming over
a waterfall of double cream.

474
00:25:56,800 --> 00:25:59,520
A luxurious waterfall, too.

475
00:25:59,560 --> 00:26:05,480
The 760 has seats that
massage you, and an SAS-spec
night-vision system.

476
00:26:07,720 --> 00:26:09,520
And here's a clever thing.

477
00:26:09,560 --> 00:26:11,920
I'm pulling up
to this junction,
the view is quite obstructed,

478
00:26:11,960 --> 00:26:13,840
I can't really
see what's coming.

479
00:26:13,880 --> 00:26:15,480
But if I press this button,

480
00:26:15,520 --> 00:26:17,720
there are little cameras
mounted on the wings

481
00:26:17,760 --> 00:26:22,160
that give you eyes on the side
of your head.
It's like being a rabbit.

482
00:26:22,200 --> 00:26:27,240
And the price?
A smudge under £100,000.

483
00:26:27,280 --> 00:26:29,520
If you have that sort of money
to spend on a car,

484
00:26:29,560 --> 00:26:33,560
there's a good chance you'll
want to pay somebody to
drive it for you.

485
00:26:33,600 --> 00:26:37,760
So that's
exactly what I've done,
I've got myself a chauffeur.

486
00:26:37,800 --> 00:26:39,520
He's in a bit of a bad mood
to be honest,

487
00:26:39,560 --> 00:26:41,480
because I've told him
this is my test.

488
00:26:41,520 --> 00:26:44,360
It's not about tyre smoke
and going sideways.

489
00:26:44,400 --> 00:26:47,680
Dignified
driving is what I want.

490
00:26:47,720 --> 00:26:49,960
This version of the 7 Series
is only available

491
00:26:50,000 --> 00:26:51,840
as a long wheelbase model,

492
00:26:51,880 --> 00:26:54,600
which means you get an extra
five inches of leg
room in the back.

493
00:26:54,640 --> 00:26:58,760
Doesn't sound much, but it
makes a world of difference
and I can watch TV.

494
00:26:58,800 --> 00:27:02,200
I've got something on here,
it's interesting,
it's about antiques...

495
00:27:02,240 --> 00:27:03,720
[LOUD BANG]

496
00:27:05,440 --> 00:27:07,200
What are you doing, man?

497
00:27:11,000 --> 00:27:12,720
Bloody hell!

498
00:27:12,760 --> 00:27:16,640
Oh, God, I see the problem.
The Mercedes
S63 has turned up,

499
00:27:16,680 --> 00:27:19,680
that's the other car
I was going to test,

500
00:27:19,720 --> 00:27:22,040
and that sort of
put Stigs on heat.

501
00:27:25,960 --> 00:27:29,280
That S-Class is actually
the AMG tuned version.

502
00:27:29,320 --> 00:27:33,040
It's a bit of a rocket ship,
I can see why
Stig's got the red mist.

503
00:27:34,680 --> 00:27:36,640
Luckily,
Stig's a bit too stupid

504
00:27:36,680 --> 00:27:39,120
to work out where
all the driver
aids are on this.

505
00:27:41,360 --> 00:27:43,080
Oh, no, he's found it.

506
00:27:43,120 --> 00:27:47,200
Oh, God! Stig has put the
dynamic driving control
into sport plus.

507
00:27:47,240 --> 00:27:50,080
That sharpens up
throttle response
and gear changes!

508
00:27:50,120 --> 00:27:51,560
[TYRES SQUEAL]

509
00:27:52,120 --> 00:27:53,520
Bloody Nora!

510
00:27:57,840 --> 00:28:00,880
God,
he's switched the stability
control off altogether...

511
00:28:04,880 --> 00:28:09,240
That locks up
the rear differential
for extra.... Ow! Hooligan!

512
00:28:09,280 --> 00:28:10,520
Ow!

513
00:28:18,320 --> 00:28:24,400
So, the Mercedes.
The most powerful
non-turbo V8 car in the world.

514
00:28:24,440 --> 00:28:28,120
It costs the same as the BMW,
it comes only in
business class,

515
00:28:28,160 --> 00:28:30,360
long wheelbase form,
like the BMW,

516
00:28:30,400 --> 00:28:35,600
and like the BMW,
it's dripping with technology.

517
00:28:35,640 --> 00:28:40,680
Even the interior lighting
has three different
colour settings.

518
00:28:40,720 --> 00:28:45,200
In fact,
there's such a bewildering
array of gizmos on both cars,

519
00:28:45,240 --> 00:28:48,040
that it's almost impossible
to choose between them.

520
00:28:54,600 --> 00:28:56,720
We're going to
make it a bit easier
with a game of...

521
00:28:56,760 --> 00:28:59,120
Top Trumps.
Here's my opponent, The Stig.

522
00:28:59,160 --> 00:29:02,240
It's just like
normal Top Trumps,
except all of Stiggy's cards

523
00:29:02,280 --> 00:29:05,800
are the BMW, and all of mine
are the Mercedes. Ready?

524
00:29:07,640 --> 00:29:11,000
OK, TV screens.
Mercedes has TV in the front.

525
00:29:13,520 --> 00:29:17,160
BMW...I know
the answer to this,
it's got two, hasn't it?

526
00:29:17,200 --> 00:29:20,680
Front and rear,
so you win that pair.

527
00:29:22,280 --> 00:29:26,480
Climate control.
Mercedes - two-zone.

528
00:29:26,520 --> 00:29:29,560
And the BMW, we know,
has got four-zone
climate control,

529
00:29:29,600 --> 00:29:31,560
so you win that pair.

530
00:29:32,360 --> 00:29:34,080
It's not difficult.

531
00:29:34,120 --> 00:29:39,840
Seat massage system.
Mercedes - front
and rear seat massage.

532
00:29:39,880 --> 00:29:46,240
And the BMW, massage seat
only in the front,
so I win that pair.

533
00:29:47,000 --> 00:29:48,200
Right, bhp...

534
00:29:53,640 --> 00:29:55,880
OK, that's not working,

535
00:29:55,920 --> 00:29:59,440
so let's go back
to the traditional,
philistineTop Gear  method.

536
00:29:59,480 --> 00:30:01,920
A drag race.

537
00:30:01,960 --> 00:30:05,480
I went in the Mercedes
with Stig at the wheel.

538
00:30:05,520 --> 00:30:07,720
I think I'll
have "firm massage"
for this.

539
00:30:13,480 --> 00:30:15,720
The BMW quickly took the lead.

540
00:30:17,400 --> 00:30:19,560
And stayed there to the end.

541
00:30:20,800 --> 00:30:23,240
That made Stig so angry,
he went home.

542
00:30:25,720 --> 00:30:27,720
So, the S-Class.
When you drive it,

543
00:30:27,760 --> 00:30:32,040
you realise it's got much
more of a split
personality than the BMW.

544
00:30:33,440 --> 00:30:36,840
On the one hand, it has lots
of very civilising features,

545
00:30:36,880 --> 00:30:39,360
it has active body control,

546
00:30:39,400 --> 00:30:43,440
and it's so clever it can
detect a crosswind and
compensate for it.

547
00:30:43,480 --> 00:30:47,680
It even has a drowsiness
sensor to prevent you
from nodding off.

548
00:30:49,360 --> 00:30:52,120
But put your foot down
and suddenly it erupts

549
00:30:52,160 --> 00:30:56,040
with typical
AMG volcanic storm
and fury.

550
00:31:00,800 --> 00:31:03,040
And here's something
that really baffles me.

551
00:31:03,080 --> 00:31:06,160
On the dashboard
I have a race timer

552
00:31:06,200 --> 00:31:09,800
that allows you to record
your lap times. But why?

553
00:31:09,840 --> 00:31:14,240
I mean, in a 911 GT3, yes.
But who's that for?

554
00:31:14,280 --> 00:31:16,520
Sir Alan Sugar on a track day?

555
00:31:17,800 --> 00:31:19,680
And that's the problem
with the Mercedes,

556
00:31:19,720 --> 00:31:22,720
it has a strangely
confused personality.

557
00:31:22,760 --> 00:31:26,600
And for that reason,
Mercedes S63 AMG...

558
00:31:27,720 --> 00:31:29,640
...you're fired.

559
00:31:36,600 --> 00:31:38,600
So,
let's just get this straight.

560
00:31:38,640 --> 00:31:41,880
Quite wrongly,
you prefer the BMW.

561
00:31:41,920 --> 00:31:44,160
No, I think they're both
completely pointless.

562
00:31:44,200 --> 00:31:47,240
Couldn't agree with you more.
They are absolutely pointless.

563
00:31:47,280 --> 00:31:51,000
And now, I'm afraid,
we must dive even more deeply

564
00:31:51,040 --> 00:31:53,160
into the murky waters
of their irrelevance

565
00:31:53,200 --> 00:31:56,600
by handing them over
to our tame racing driver.

566
00:31:56,640 --> 00:32:02,360
Some say, that in the autumn,
all his arms go
brown and fall off.

567
00:32:02,400 --> 00:32:04,160
[LAUGHTER]

568
00:32:04,200 --> 00:32:06,240
And that if he wrote you
a letter of condolence,

569
00:32:06,280 --> 00:32:08,320
he would at least
get your name right.

570
00:32:08,360 --> 00:32:10,120
[SHOCKED LAUGHTER]

571
00:32:10,160 --> 00:32:13,680
- All we know is,
he's called The Stog.
- You mean The Stig.

572
00:32:13,720 --> 00:32:15,640
That's what I said.

573
00:32:16,320 --> 00:32:17,840
I said it!

574
00:32:17,880 --> 00:32:20,680
And they're off!
It is very wet out there,

575
00:32:20,720 --> 00:32:24,720
tiny wiggle of
the hips from the BMW
as the turbos spool up.

576
00:32:24,760 --> 00:32:26,560
Here's something
not very interesting,

577
00:32:26,600 --> 00:32:30,480
that 760 has
BMW's first petrol V12
with two turbos.

578
00:32:30,520 --> 00:32:35,000
That is much more
interesting there,
he's getting very sideways!

579
00:32:35,040 --> 00:32:37,120
[PIANO PLAYING]

580
00:32:39,560 --> 00:32:42,200
Yeah, I should say The Stig
is deeply saddened

581
00:32:42,240 --> 00:32:44,240
that Chas and
Dave have split up.

582
00:32:44,280 --> 00:32:46,800
This is his way of
getting through the pain.

583
00:32:46,840 --> 00:32:49,240
God! That BMW is
very sideways there,

584
00:32:49,280 --> 00:32:51,280
coming up to the Hammerhead

585
00:32:51,320 --> 00:32:54,960
we're expecting
understeer here
from these two-tonne barges.

586
00:32:55,000 --> 00:32:57,720
And, yep, the 7 Series
is ploughing wide,

587
00:32:57,760 --> 00:32:59,880
Merc more composed.

588
00:32:59,920 --> 00:33:03,720
I suspect because
the traction control
can't be fully switched off.

589
00:33:03,760 --> 00:33:07,960
Here we are, Follow-through.
It really is wet out there.

590
00:33:08,000 --> 00:33:11,200
Stig would be better off
in an actual barge, I think.

591
00:33:11,240 --> 00:33:12,960
Quick through the tyres,

592
00:33:13,000 --> 00:33:15,360
look up "brave"
in the dictionary
it says, "See The Stig".

593
00:33:15,400 --> 00:33:16,760
Two corners left.

594
00:33:16,800 --> 00:33:18,560
BMW's all over the shop.

595
00:33:18,600 --> 00:33:20,240
That let the S-Class ahead,

596
00:33:20,280 --> 00:33:22,480
but they're evenly matched
coming through Gambon!

597
00:33:22,520 --> 00:33:24,040
Across the line!

598
00:33:24,080 --> 00:33:25,880
[APPLAUSE]

599
00:33:25,920 --> 00:33:28,200
- Does it go here?
- No, it doesn't.

600
00:33:28,920 --> 00:33:30,440
Does it go here?

601
00:33:30,480 --> 00:33:32,520
No, it doesn't.

602
00:33:32,560 --> 00:33:33,760
Go on, then.

603
00:33:33,800 --> 00:33:37,160
Right, the Mercedes S63 did it
in 1.32.1.

604
00:33:37,200 --> 00:33:38,840
The BMW did it in...

605
00:33:38,880 --> 00:33:42,200
1.31.2

606
00:33:42,240 --> 00:33:44,600
There we are.
If you are a banker

607
00:33:44,640 --> 00:33:48,440
and you like to get anywhere
in a big hurry,
go for the BMW.

608
00:33:48,480 --> 00:33:50,480
Consumer advice for you there.

609
00:33:50,520 --> 00:33:54,600
Now, it is time to put a star
in our reasonably priced car.

610
00:33:54,640 --> 00:33:58,360
My guest tonight, it seems,
always wanted to
be a racing driver,

611
00:33:58,400 --> 00:34:02,320
but then he
accidentally ended up
being in films like

612
00:34:02,360 --> 00:34:04,920
Star Trek, Finding Nemo,

613
00:34:04,960 --> 00:34:09,800
Black Hawk Down, Troy,
and so on and so forth.

614
00:34:09,840 --> 00:34:12,480
So, here to find out
what on earth went wrong,

615
00:34:12,520 --> 00:34:16,080
from somewhere called
Australia, ladies
and gentlemen, Eric Bana!

616
00:34:16,120 --> 00:34:18,080
[APPLAUSE AND CHEERING]

617
00:34:19,800 --> 00:34:21,680
Good to see you, how are you?

618
00:34:21,720 --> 00:34:23,640
- Very well, very well.
- Have a seat.

619
00:34:25,400 --> 00:34:27,600
A proper superstar is here!

620
00:34:28,600 --> 00:34:30,080
What's in there?

621
00:34:30,120 --> 00:34:31,720
There?

622
00:34:31,760 --> 00:34:34,240
It's water,
it's OK, it won't have
anything dangerous in it.

623
00:34:34,280 --> 00:34:35,760
Yeah, just water.

624
00:34:35,800 --> 00:34:37,880
This Bathurst Motor Race
we were talking about earlier,

625
00:34:37,920 --> 00:34:39,720
have you heard
about the beer thing?

626
00:34:39,760 --> 00:34:44,920
They're limiting the amount
of beer each fan can take
to 24 cans a day.

627
00:34:44,960 --> 00:34:46,400
That's a serious restriction.

628
00:34:46,440 --> 00:34:48,120
[LAUGHTER]

629
00:34:48,160 --> 00:34:51,160
That's
practically teetotalling,
isn't it?

630
00:34:51,200 --> 00:34:55,000
This rivalry
between Ford and GM,

631
00:34:55,040 --> 00:34:57,560
it's ingrained from birth,
isn't it, in all Australians?

632
00:34:57,600 --> 00:34:59,480
It's pretty deep-seated.

633
00:34:59,520 --> 00:35:03,680
They were the two
main manufacturers,
if you're my age,

634
00:35:03,720 --> 00:35:05,040
when you were growing up.

635
00:35:05,080 --> 00:35:07,040
It was, you know,
the General Motors product

636
00:35:07,080 --> 00:35:09,240
which was Holden,
Commodores and Toranas

637
00:35:09,280 --> 00:35:11,280
and for me it was Falcons.

638
00:35:11,320 --> 00:35:13,320
I said to the two guys,

639
00:35:13,360 --> 00:35:15,800
the two Aussies who are here
in the audience somewhere,

640
00:35:15,840 --> 00:35:18,280
"Eric Bana's coming on,"
they went "Ah, Ford bloke."

641
00:35:18,320 --> 00:35:20,480
That was it.
You're a Ford bloke
therefore you're no good.

642
00:35:20,520 --> 00:35:22,480
Cos you're a Ford bloke
and they're Holden blokes.

643
00:35:22,520 --> 00:35:24,480
- Completely
discounted me, huh?
- Yeah, exactly.

644
00:35:24,520 --> 00:35:28,720
It seems to me that Bathurst
combines everything, really,

645
00:35:28,760 --> 00:35:30,480
that you need in Australia.

646
00:35:30,520 --> 00:35:34,120
Outside cooking, obviously.
Drinking and sport.

647
00:35:34,160 --> 00:35:37,920
This sport thing, it's weird,
cos you're no
good at it, so...

648
00:35:37,960 --> 00:35:39,520
Oh, really?

649
00:35:39,560 --> 00:35:40,680
- Really?
- Well...

650
00:35:40,720 --> 00:35:42,480
Cite a couple of examples.

651
00:35:42,520 --> 00:35:44,040
The Ashes.

652
00:35:44,080 --> 00:35:46,480
The most recent one,
the most recent one.

653
00:35:46,520 --> 00:35:48,520
- Rugby, the other day?
- Didn't we
beat you last week?

654
00:35:48,560 --> 00:35:52,680
We weren't playing!
It was Jonny
Wilkinson and some lawyers.

655
00:35:52,720 --> 00:35:54,480
- Mm.
- [LAUGHTER]

656
00:35:54,520 --> 00:35:57,360
The best thing about having
an Aussie here is...

657
00:35:57,400 --> 00:35:59,360
and I don't know
if it's the same
with Australia,

658
00:35:59,400 --> 00:36:02,720
is there are very few
countrymen or countrywomen

659
00:36:02,760 --> 00:36:04,760
that we can tease
and get joshing...

660
00:36:04,800 --> 00:36:07,520
Australia and England, it
seems to me, are the last two
countries on Earth

661
00:36:07,560 --> 00:36:09,000
where you can go there and go,

662
00:36:09,040 --> 00:36:11,280
"hide my wallet
under the soap,
he won't find it there."

663
00:36:11,320 --> 00:36:16,280
If you go up to an American
and say, "You lost
in Vietnam..." [LAUGHS]

664
00:36:16,320 --> 00:36:18,120
They just don't
find that funny.

665
00:36:18,160 --> 00:36:20,120
I mean, to be quite honest,
we're happy,

666
00:36:20,160 --> 00:36:22,560
we ended up in
the best country.
So, it's...

667
00:36:22,600 --> 00:36:25,880
So it's not like
it's second prize
as far as you are concerned.

668
00:36:25,920 --> 00:36:27,080
It's quite dangerous,
though, Australia.

669
00:36:27,120 --> 00:36:28,200
Why?

670
00:36:28,240 --> 00:36:30,560
- I don't know.
How old are you?
- 41.

671
00:36:30,600 --> 00:36:33,120
You must be the oldest
Australian who hasn't been
eaten by a shark

672
00:36:33,160 --> 00:36:36,960
- or bitten by a spider.
- There's a few around,
you know...

673
00:36:37,000 --> 00:36:40,520
That's what happens when
you have great beaches.
[LAUGHS]

674
00:36:42,440 --> 00:36:43,600
We've got great beaches.

675
00:36:43,640 --> 00:36:46,280
Oh, you do, yeah!
Awesome surf, too.

676
00:36:46,320 --> 00:36:50,120
- At least we have nice names.
- Give me an example.

677
00:36:50,160 --> 00:36:53,600
Cos the thing I genuinely love
about Australia is
the literal names.

678
00:36:53,640 --> 00:36:56,040
"We've got this big sandy
desert in the middle.
What shall we call it?

679
00:36:56,080 --> 00:36:58,520
"Ah! The Great Sandy Desert.
We've got this reef

680
00:36:58,560 --> 00:37:02,320
"off the coast,
it's like a barrier,
the Great Barrier Reef."

681
00:37:02,360 --> 00:37:05,120
This is of course
as opposed to...

682
00:37:05,160 --> 00:37:07,000
- the White Cliffs of Dover...
- Yeah.

683
00:37:07,040 --> 00:37:10,840
- Green Park.
- Yeah,
Green Park isn't very good.

684
00:37:10,880 --> 00:37:12,280
Four Weddings And A Funeral.

685
00:37:12,320 --> 00:37:14,000
That wasn't a very good...
What about  Mad Max?

686
00:37:14,040 --> 00:37:16,560
"It's about a bloke who's mad
and he's called Max."

687
00:37:16,600 --> 00:37:18,920
Perfect title.

688
00:37:18,960 --> 00:37:20,560
I want to get on
to the car thing,

689
00:37:20,600 --> 00:37:23,840
cos let's be honest,
this proper
love that you have,

690
00:37:23,880 --> 00:37:28,200
cos you are now a bona fide
Australian racing driver.

691
00:37:28,240 --> 00:37:31,840
I just have a bit of fun
in the Australian GT series,

692
00:37:31,880 --> 00:37:36,680
which is like your version of,
it'd be FAA, GT3 racing,

693
00:37:36,720 --> 00:37:38,920
so I'm in
a Porsche Cup car, 911.

694
00:37:38,960 --> 00:37:42,080
So you're pretty good,
it's not like
you're some actor who's...

695
00:37:42,120 --> 00:37:45,320
I don't know. I enjoy it
and I'd never stop doing it,

696
00:37:45,360 --> 00:37:48,240
- I'm just,
you know, I'm obsessed.
- Do you define your life...?

697
00:37:48,280 --> 00:37:51,760
Do you say, "I'm not gonna do
that film cos I really
wanna do that race?"

698
00:37:51,800 --> 00:37:53,600
[QUIETLY] Is
this on in America?

699
00:37:53,640 --> 00:37:56,160
No.
America is the only country
in the world this isn't shown.

700
00:37:56,200 --> 00:37:58,120
Of course I've done that!
Are you kidding me?!

701
00:37:58,160 --> 00:38:01,360
[LAUGHTER AND APPLAUSE]

702
00:38:01,400 --> 00:38:03,160
Good man!

703
00:38:03,200 --> 00:38:05,720
Everywhere else in the world
will hear that,
but not America.

704
00:38:05,760 --> 00:38:07,400
They'll never find out.

705
00:38:07,440 --> 00:38:11,440
If I could just say,
you've been in
some massive films,

706
00:38:11,480 --> 00:38:13,440
but the one that seems to me

707
00:38:13,480 --> 00:38:15,720
to be closest to your heart is
the one that you've just
brought out now,

708
00:38:15,760 --> 00:38:17,560
which is  Love The Beast.

709
00:38:17,600 --> 00:38:19,840
Love The Beast.

710
00:38:19,880 --> 00:38:22,680
Tell me about that, because
it's a very small film
compared to, let's say,  Troy.

711
00:38:22,720 --> 00:38:25,760
Well, it is.
It's
a documentary that I directed.

712
00:38:25,800 --> 00:38:30,400
One day,
I was looking at my beast,
which is my Ford Falcon Coupe.

713
00:38:30,440 --> 00:38:32,920
And I'd had this
car since I was 15.
And I thought,

714
00:38:32,960 --> 00:38:39,000
this actually isn't a car.
This is like some kind of
a personal, um, possession

715
00:38:39,040 --> 00:38:42,800
that gets carted around
through all kinds of
different circumstances,

716
00:38:42,840 --> 00:38:47,520
and I started
thinking more and more
about that, and how cars,

717
00:38:47,560 --> 00:38:50,600
objects, in particular cars,
I think, I feel,
can transcend themselves

718
00:38:50,640 --> 00:38:53,680
to become something else.
I feel deeply about it.

719
00:38:53,720 --> 00:38:56,040
- I couldn't agree more.
- Right.

720
00:38:56,080 --> 00:38:58,720
I really do believe that cars
take on a personality.

721
00:38:58,760 --> 00:39:00,440
Not all cars, but some do.

722
00:39:00,480 --> 00:39:04,680
So this film is about
your
relationship with this car?

723
00:39:04,720 --> 00:39:09,240
Yeah, and then I was competing
in Targa Tasmania that year,

724
00:39:09,280 --> 00:39:13,240
so I thought,
"We'll just make the rally
a bit of an action backdrop

725
00:39:13,280 --> 00:39:17,200
"to this story
about a guy having a car
for his whole life."

726
00:39:17,240 --> 00:39:19,040
- Having
a relationship with a car?
- Yeah.

727
00:39:19,080 --> 00:39:21,560
OK, we've got a clip here
which I'd like to show
everyone. Here we go.

728
00:39:21,600 --> 00:39:24,080
TANNOY:
Three...two...one...go!

729
00:39:25,680 --> 00:39:27,560
[HEAVY ROCK MUSIC]

730
00:39:29,800 --> 00:39:31,480
And then a five left.

731
00:39:33,280 --> 00:39:34,840
It's slippery, apparently.

732
00:39:34,880 --> 00:39:36,720
I feel like I'm
breaking in a horse.

733
00:39:36,760 --> 00:39:38,840
I feel like
every day both horses
are learning, me and the car.

734
00:39:38,880 --> 00:39:41,120
OK, left,
right, we need to stay on it.

735
00:39:41,160 --> 00:39:45,080
Six left.
Caution, one-two right, 100.

736
00:39:45,120 --> 00:39:46,520
Car up here.

737
00:39:46,560 --> 00:39:48,080
[TYRES SCREECH]

738
00:39:48,880 --> 00:39:50,320
[CRASH]

739
00:39:50,360 --> 00:39:51,720
Jeez!

740
00:39:51,760 --> 00:39:53,840
- [APPLAUSE]
- Did that hurt?

741
00:39:54,480 --> 00:39:55,800
Um...

742
00:39:57,760 --> 00:40:00,760
I think what hurt the most was
just knowing that
it was gonna happen,

743
00:40:00,800 --> 00:40:02,600
you know, before it happened.

744
00:40:02,640 --> 00:40:05,120
I could have told you that!
Cos if you've
got a muscle car,

745
00:40:05,160 --> 00:40:08,440
you go round a corner,
you're gonna hit a tree!

746
00:40:08,480 --> 00:40:13,560
Now,
you were wondering whether
to rebuild that car... again.

747
00:40:13,600 --> 00:40:17,520
True. One of the things I was
facing... Whilst I was
shooting the documentary,

748
00:40:17,560 --> 00:40:20,360
I never planned on
crashing
the bloody car, obviously!

749
00:40:20,400 --> 00:40:23,320
...was, I'd killed it,
basically, and then for
a couple of months,

750
00:40:23,360 --> 00:40:28,000
we thought that it was dead
and we couldn't,
in fact, repair it.

751
00:40:28,040 --> 00:40:31,560
I decided that if it
required a re-shell,

752
00:40:31,600 --> 00:40:33,520
then I would not
rebuild the car.

753
00:40:33,560 --> 00:40:35,120
- But does it?
- It doesn't.

754
00:40:35,160 --> 00:40:36,880
It doesn't?
So you're going to
rebuild it again?

755
00:40:36,920 --> 00:40:38,400
We're going to
rebuild it again.

756
00:40:38,440 --> 00:40:40,600
You do realise everything
you earn from  Star Trek

757
00:40:40,640 --> 00:40:44,960
will be lost the next time you
try to go round a corner when
you've rebuilt it?

758
00:40:45,000 --> 00:40:46,520
Yeah.

759
00:40:46,560 --> 00:40:49,920
Now,
obviously, you didn't come
thousands of miles

760
00:40:49,960 --> 00:40:52,160
to just sit and
talk about this.

761
00:40:52,200 --> 00:40:56,280
You came to
have a go out there
in the reasonably priced car.

762
00:40:56,320 --> 00:40:57,520
So, how was it?

763
00:40:57,560 --> 00:41:00,320
It was slippery,
but it was a lot of fun.

764
00:41:00,360 --> 00:41:04,360
It's been a while
since I've driven
such a reasonably priced car.

765
00:41:04,400 --> 00:41:05,920
[LAUGHTER]

766
00:41:05,960 --> 00:41:08,160
Who would like
to see Eric's lap?

767
00:41:08,200 --> 00:41:09,480
ALL: Yes!

768
00:41:09,520 --> 00:41:11,080
Let's have a look!

769
00:41:11,120 --> 00:41:13,760
- [TYRES SKID]
- JEREMY:  Thatis  slippery.

770
00:41:13,800 --> 00:41:19,000
I'll never play Test cricket,
but I'll drive
the  Top Geartrack!

771
00:41:19,040 --> 00:41:20,640
[LAUGHTER]

772
00:41:20,680 --> 00:41:22,840
JEREMY:  First corner, now...

773
00:41:22,880 --> 00:41:26,000
Ooh, you see, there's somebody
who knows how to drive,
look at that!

774
00:41:27,720 --> 00:41:30,840
Feel the grip from
the reasonably
priced Lacetti now.

775
00:41:31,480 --> 00:41:32,720
Get over!

776
00:41:34,760 --> 00:41:36,720
JEREMY:
Were you really putting
your heart and soul into this?

777
00:41:36,760 --> 00:41:38,800
- Um...
- Yes, you were!

778
00:41:38,840 --> 00:41:41,560
I won't pretend I don't care
what my lap time is.

779
00:41:41,600 --> 00:41:43,960
Get out of the way, birds!

780
00:41:44,000 --> 00:41:46,160
JEREMY:
Look, non-dangerous birds.

781
00:41:46,200 --> 00:41:48,320
Not like those ones
that burst on your windscreen,

782
00:41:48,360 --> 00:41:51,520
showering you in worms,
which is what
happens in Australia.

783
00:41:51,560 --> 00:41:55,120
- Ooh,
bit of understeer there.
- Lots of understeer there.

784
00:41:56,800 --> 00:41:57,640
JEREMY:  Time to put it away.

785
00:41:57,680 --> 00:41:58,720
Oh, you sluts!

786
00:41:58,760 --> 00:42:00,480
Gearbox, sorry about that.

787
00:42:00,520 --> 00:42:04,240
Hasn't mended. Follow-through,
were you flat through there?

788
00:42:04,280 --> 00:42:05,680
Flat.

789
00:42:05,720 --> 00:42:08,480
And flat through the tyres,
I'm guessing.

790
00:42:08,520 --> 00:42:10,960
Yep,
that looks pretty flat to me.

791
00:42:11,000 --> 00:42:13,200
Now, second to last corner,
this is the tricky one.

792
00:42:13,240 --> 00:42:15,080
I don't think I ever
got this one right.

793
00:42:15,120 --> 00:42:17,680
Let's have a look.
You've got to
cut it a bit... Yes, perfect.

794
00:42:17,720 --> 00:42:20,120
Now, just Gambon.

795
00:42:20,160 --> 00:42:22,640
Ooh, that's quite
legal through there.
Most people cheat.

796
00:42:22,680 --> 00:42:24,880
There we are, across the line!

797
00:42:25,480 --> 00:42:26,840
[APPLAUSE]

798
00:42:27,400 --> 00:42:28,520
Aha!

799
00:42:30,080 --> 00:42:35,680
Now, bearing in mind that
that was a wet lap...

800
00:42:35,720 --> 00:42:39,440
Yeah, it was very slippery.
I was waiting for
it to dry out, but...

801
00:42:39,480 --> 00:42:42,400
All right!
That's enough excuses!
It's a wet lap.

802
00:42:42,440 --> 00:42:43,840
You were being
a racing driver there.

803
00:42:43,880 --> 00:42:46,400
I'm just looking for
the fastest ever wet lap,

804
00:42:46,440 --> 00:42:50,840
which,
I think, from what I can see,
is Jamie Oliver on 1.47.7.

805
00:42:50,880 --> 00:42:53,400
I'm in two minds.
I'd like to beat him,

806
00:42:53,440 --> 00:42:55,480
but my wife loves him.

807
00:42:55,520 --> 00:42:57,880
- [LAUGHTER]
- Eric Bana,

808
00:42:58,760 --> 00:43:00,720
you did it in 1...

809
00:43:02,440 --> 00:43:03,680
...40...

810
00:43:04,840 --> 00:43:07,840
- ...7...
- [GASPING]

811
00:43:07,880 --> 00:43:11,640
...5.
There you go, mate!
You did it!

812
00:43:11,680 --> 00:43:14,720
I'd better put
a "wet" on that.

813
00:43:14,760 --> 00:43:18,360
- That is
the fastest wet lap...
- Whoo!

814
00:43:18,400 --> 00:43:20,360
...we've ever had.

815
00:43:20,400 --> 00:43:22,000
The fastest.

816
00:43:23,520 --> 00:43:28,640
You are 0.2 of a second
faster than a chef.

817
00:43:28,680 --> 00:43:29,960
[LAUGHTER]

818
00:43:30,000 --> 00:43:31,800
But you are
the fastest Australian.

819
00:43:31,840 --> 00:43:36,440
Is there a wet-track Ashes
that I can take
back to Australia?

820
00:43:36,480 --> 00:43:40,080
Tell you what we'll do. We'll
burn the car and put it
in a little thing,

821
00:43:40,120 --> 00:43:41,760
and you can take it back
and Australia can

822
00:43:41,800 --> 00:43:43,480
have some ashes for
the next few years.

823
00:43:43,520 --> 00:43:44,680
All right.

824
00:43:44,720 --> 00:43:47,040
Ladies and gentlemen,
Eric Bana!

825
00:43:47,080 --> 00:43:49,000
[CHEERING AND APPLAUSE]

826
00:43:53,480 --> 00:43:57,880
Now,
tonight we're in Romania...

827
00:43:57,920 --> 00:44:00,080
looking for the best road
in the world.

828
00:44:00,120 --> 00:44:03,280
We're driving an Aston Martin,
a Ferrari and a Lamborghini

829
00:44:03,320 --> 00:44:06,360
and so far we'd each decided
that our car was the best.

830
00:44:06,400 --> 00:44:10,720
James had got lost,
and we'd ended up
by mistake in Bucharest.

831
00:44:21,880 --> 00:44:25,280
JAMES:
We left Bucharest the next
morning and headed west,

832
00:44:25,320 --> 00:44:30,040
still full of wonderment for
this amazing
country and our cars.

833
00:44:32,320 --> 00:44:36,320
This car is actually filling
me with a sort of
primordial lust.

834
00:44:36,360 --> 00:44:40,040
It actually tingles down
in my bowels. It's sinful.

835
00:44:41,920 --> 00:44:44,560
I cannot tell you
how joyful it is

836
00:44:44,600 --> 00:44:49,800
to drive a V12 sports car
with a proper manual gearbox.

837
00:44:51,960 --> 00:44:55,400
Manual gearbox,
really, in a GT car?

838
00:44:55,440 --> 00:44:57,840
D'you want that?
It's about making
your life easier.

839
00:44:57,880 --> 00:45:00,840
Fast, but easier
and more comfortable.

840
00:45:00,880 --> 00:45:03,120
If you're gonna go GT-ing...

841
00:45:03,840 --> 00:45:05,680
...Ferrari, surely?

842
00:45:10,160 --> 00:45:12,080
JEREMY:  Then disaster.

843
00:45:12,120 --> 00:45:15,200
Romania only has
143 miles of motorway

844
00:45:15,240 --> 00:45:19,440
and by 11am
we'd used every one of them.

845
00:45:19,480 --> 00:45:23,200
Ah, James, policemen.
Many, many
traditions and rituals...

846
00:45:23,240 --> 00:45:25,000
OVER RADIO:
...surrounding policemen.
Amongst them,

847
00:45:25,040 --> 00:45:28,560
if he has a gun,
you must go and
just unbutton it,

848
00:45:28,600 --> 00:45:30,440
just because that says,
"I trust you

849
00:45:30,480 --> 00:45:32,680
"with your weapon."
Go and unbutton the holster.

850
00:45:32,720 --> 00:45:34,400
JEREMY:  Righto!

851
00:45:34,440 --> 00:45:38,120
No, just knock
his hat off, James.
They think it's funny.

852
00:45:38,160 --> 00:45:42,080
They often express
their humour here
with gunfire. [CHUCKLES]

853
00:45:44,160 --> 00:45:47,920
We then told
James we were stopping
to put our wind deflectors up.

854
00:45:47,960 --> 00:45:50,880
But, in fact, the real reason
we stopped here

855
00:45:50,920 --> 00:45:53,600
is so that I could give him
a surprise present.

856
00:45:54,440 --> 00:45:55,680
Oh, God!

857
00:45:56,560 --> 00:45:57,920
Is it an ox?

858
00:45:57,960 --> 00:46:01,040
- Is it a Gypsy? A big one?
- Nope.

859
00:46:01,720 --> 00:46:03,320
It's over there.

860
00:46:04,640 --> 00:46:07,160
- What, some wood?
- In front of the wood.

861
00:46:08,000 --> 00:46:09,360
- No!
- Yep.

862
00:46:09,400 --> 00:46:10,640
Seriously.

863
00:46:10,680 --> 00:46:13,040
I have bought you -
it's second hand -

864
00:46:13,080 --> 00:46:16,440
but I have bought you
a Dacia Sandero.

865
00:46:16,480 --> 00:46:18,200
- Really?
- Yes.

866
00:46:18,240 --> 00:46:20,280
- Oh, mate!
- Seriously,
that's my Dacia Sandero?

867
00:46:20,320 --> 00:46:22,960
Yes. No piano's
going to land on it,
it's not a Morris Marina.

868
00:46:23,000 --> 00:46:24,960
- JAMES: I'm quite touched.
- RICHARD: That's fantastic!

869
00:46:25,000 --> 00:46:27,000
- Can I drive it?
- You go off and drive it

870
00:46:27,040 --> 00:46:29,840
- while we're
putting these on.
- All right.

871
00:46:29,880 --> 00:46:33,720
RICHARD: He's
genuinely chuffed to bits!

872
00:46:33,760 --> 00:46:36,600
For two years, I've been
dreaming about this car,

873
00:46:36,640 --> 00:46:39,840
and now I was
actually driving it.

874
00:46:39,880 --> 00:46:42,080
The Lamborghini
is all very well,

875
00:46:42,120 --> 00:46:44,680
that's like
the ultimate expression
of what a car can be,

876
00:46:44,720 --> 00:46:47,080
but this is
the essence of a car.

877
00:46:47,120 --> 00:46:50,600
All the bits you need,
nothing more.
No flimflam.

878
00:46:50,640 --> 00:46:53,120
This is a bit of a faff,
isn't it?

879
00:46:53,160 --> 00:46:57,720
Ah! A cool, refreshing
communist water.

880
00:46:58,320 --> 00:46:59,200
Jeez!

881
00:47:00,880 --> 00:47:03,240
I could buy that for Hammond,
that could be his present.

882
00:47:05,120 --> 00:47:06,400
Listen to this!

883
00:47:06,440 --> 00:47:08,480
[ENGINE WARBLES]

884
00:47:08,520 --> 00:47:12,880
Nice throaty little warble
from the engine.
It's a happy car.

885
00:47:12,920 --> 00:47:16,040
Dacia Sandero.
That is an excellent present.

886
00:47:16,080 --> 00:47:17,800
I don't know what
he was thinking of there,

887
00:47:17,840 --> 00:47:19,680
cos his presents are supposed
to be irritating,

888
00:47:19,720 --> 00:47:23,840
but that's not irritating.
That's superb!

889
00:47:23,880 --> 00:47:25,760
Could you see anything
in your screen?

890
00:47:25,800 --> 00:47:27,840
- Nothing. Nothing.
- When the roof's down?

891
00:47:27,880 --> 00:47:29,320
As soon as the roof's down,
the slightest hint

892
00:47:29,360 --> 00:47:30,760
of sun behind it, it's gone.

893
00:47:30,800 --> 00:47:32,720
You're back! How is it?

894
00:47:32,760 --> 00:47:35,520
Good fun.
Great. Basic, small, rorty.

895
00:47:35,560 --> 00:47:39,280
But you haven't got
the little side joke,
have you?

896
00:47:39,320 --> 00:47:41,080
What?

897
00:47:41,120 --> 00:47:42,320
- You can't take it
back hand luggage.
- I'll drive it back.

898
00:47:42,360 --> 00:47:43,600
- RICHARD: All the way?
- Yeah.

899
00:47:43,640 --> 00:47:45,320
It took 2½ days
to get here in...

900
00:47:45,360 --> 00:47:46,800
JAMES: No!

901
00:47:48,640 --> 00:47:50,520
- Stop!
- [JEREMY GUFFAWS]

902
00:47:51,120 --> 00:47:52,320
Stop!

903
00:47:52,360 --> 00:47:54,440
- My car's parked there.
- [MAN SPEAKS ROMANIAN]

904
00:47:54,480 --> 00:47:57,760
You're supposed to look.
Look! Mirrors!

905
00:47:58,720 --> 00:48:01,280
[SPEAKS IN ROMANIAN]

906
00:48:01,320 --> 00:48:03,560
My arse! You just backed
straight into it, man!

907
00:48:03,600 --> 00:48:05,840
JEREMY: Why did you leave it
parked behind a lorry?

908
00:48:05,880 --> 00:48:07,440
I didn't know
there was anybody in it.

909
00:48:07,480 --> 00:48:10,160
I was leaving it out of shot.

910
00:48:10,200 --> 00:48:12,560
- I've only had it
about half an hour.
- Yeah.

911
00:48:12,600 --> 00:48:16,920
I think he was saying,
in Hungarian,
or whatever it is,

912
00:48:16,960 --> 00:48:19,560
it's my fault for
parking the car.

913
00:48:19,600 --> 00:48:21,560
- RICHARD: Probably was.
- JEREMY: It sort of is.

914
00:48:23,040 --> 00:48:25,040
- JAMES: Jeez!
- [RICHARD CHUCKLES]

915
00:48:26,400 --> 00:48:27,960
JEREMY: Oh, well...

916
00:48:28,000 --> 00:48:30,160
You'd have used it for work
and everything, wouldn't you?

917
00:48:30,200 --> 00:48:33,640
- Why don't you go away?
- It would've been
your everyday car.

918
00:48:33,680 --> 00:48:35,040
It would have made you happy.

919
00:48:35,080 --> 00:48:36,760
There's an old
tradition in this country

920
00:48:36,800 --> 00:48:40,800
that on the third Wednesday of
every month,
which is what today is,

921
00:48:40,840 --> 00:48:42,320
people with a black T-shirt on

922
00:48:42,360 --> 00:48:44,840
and a picture of a stupid
Russian spark plug shut up.

923
00:48:48,400 --> 00:48:50,600
I liked the Dacia Sandero.

924
00:48:50,640 --> 00:48:52,600
It was honest and simple.

925
00:48:52,640 --> 00:48:54,160
It was refreshing.

926
00:48:55,400 --> 00:48:57,800
It's broken.

927
00:48:57,840 --> 00:48:59,800
RICHARD:
As we travelled further west,

928
00:48:59,840 --> 00:49:03,680
the high-tech,
modern Romania we knew
ran out.

929
00:49:05,920 --> 00:49:08,240
It's getting a bit more...

930
00:49:08,280 --> 00:49:10,520
Borat round here.

931
00:49:10,560 --> 00:49:12,560
JEREMY:
It's Gypsy country here.

932
00:49:12,600 --> 00:49:17,800
I am told they can be a bit
violent if they don't
like the look of you.

933
00:49:17,840 --> 00:49:22,280
RICHARD:  And on top of that,
guess who was
leading the convoy?

934
00:49:22,320 --> 00:49:26,200
JAMES: I'm gonna take a punt
on going right now.

935
00:49:26,240 --> 00:49:28,080
RICHARD: Do we know
that this is the right way?

936
00:49:28,120 --> 00:49:30,920
Oh, sorry, Hammond,
I'm just following May.

937
00:49:30,960 --> 00:49:34,480
You do know
what you just said,
don't you?

938
00:49:34,520 --> 00:49:38,120
This road is becoming
alarmingly lumpy.

939
00:49:38,160 --> 00:49:40,240
I'm worried about
my Reventon-style nose.

940
00:49:41,360 --> 00:49:43,160
The nose is too low.

941
00:49:43,200 --> 00:49:46,360
He's gonna have to admit
he's brought the wrong car.

942
00:49:46,400 --> 00:49:49,560
RICHARD:
Soon, we were really lost.

943
00:49:49,600 --> 00:49:53,640
They're building
what can only be...
Yes, it's a public execution.

944
00:49:53,680 --> 00:49:57,440
Where on the map does it say,
"Turn right at
the partially built gallows"?

945
00:49:57,480 --> 00:49:58,760
That woman has an axe.

946
00:49:58,800 --> 00:50:01,560
That big woman has an axe.
She has an axe.

947
00:50:01,600 --> 00:50:04,600
JEREMY:
We drove deeper and deeper
into Borat country,

948
00:50:04,640 --> 00:50:09,000
but,
luckily, I bought something
that would help me blend in.

949
00:50:11,040 --> 00:50:15,160
I'm wearing this hat
so Gypsies think I am one...

950
00:50:15,200 --> 00:50:18,160
and that's fine.
I'm just a lucky Gypsy.

951
00:50:18,880 --> 00:50:21,520
A Pools-winning Gypsy.

952
00:50:21,560 --> 00:50:25,160
James said
the next turning would
take us back to the main road.

953
00:50:25,720 --> 00:50:27,480
It didn't.

954
00:50:27,520 --> 00:50:29,000
[EXCITED SHOUTING]

955
00:50:30,000 --> 00:50:31,600
Holy moly!

956
00:50:31,640 --> 00:50:33,760
RICHARD: Oh, yeah!

957
00:50:35,400 --> 00:50:38,080
Oh, no, wait.
If we look
what's behind you...

958
00:50:40,000 --> 00:50:42,200
Yeah, the evidence
is not stacking up!

959
00:50:42,240 --> 00:50:44,160
- Is this the horse and cart?
- That's a horse.

960
00:50:44,200 --> 00:50:46,840
JEREMY:  We wanted to hit James
over the head with a hammer,

961
00:50:46,880 --> 00:50:49,600
but the kids beat us to it.

962
00:50:49,640 --> 00:50:51,240
- [CHILDREN GIGGLING]
- Ow! Ow! Ow!

963
00:50:53,200 --> 00:50:54,960
Are you seeing this?

964
00:50:55,520 --> 00:50:57,120
[ENGINE REVS]

965
00:50:59,280 --> 00:51:02,240
Did you shrink the man
in the car behind?

966
00:51:02,280 --> 00:51:05,360
Did you shrink
that man, Gypsies?

967
00:51:05,400 --> 00:51:07,800
RICHARD:
Getting through the village
was bad enough,

968
00:51:07,840 --> 00:51:10,160
getting out of it
was even trickier.

969
00:51:11,280 --> 00:51:13,480
Oh, my God, you're joking!

970
00:51:13,520 --> 00:51:15,440
[CREAKING]

971
00:51:15,480 --> 00:51:18,280
JEREMY: Please fall off!
Please
fall off! Please fall off!

972
00:51:18,320 --> 00:51:22,800
OK, this is certainly
a Grand Tour for these cars.

973
00:51:22,840 --> 00:51:26,120
JAMES:  But with the village
behind us and armed with
some directions,

974
00:51:26,160 --> 00:51:28,600
it was plain sailing
back to the main road.

975
00:51:32,160 --> 00:51:33,160
[CRASH]

976
00:51:38,040 --> 00:51:42,160
OVER RADIO:  We have
an incident at the end of
the road with another car.

977
00:51:44,320 --> 00:51:46,680
JAMES:  Thankfully,
the damage was light.

978
00:51:46,720 --> 00:51:47,840
- My hat!
- The washer bottle.

979
00:51:47,880 --> 00:51:50,040
Yeah, it smells of detergent.

980
00:51:50,080 --> 00:51:52,640
Is everybody all
right in that car?

981
00:51:52,680 --> 00:51:56,320
- That's his
second bit of bad luck.
- Whose?

982
00:51:56,360 --> 00:51:58,480
James's.
That's his
second car of the day.

983
00:51:58,520 --> 00:52:00,240
Yeah! James...

984
00:52:00,280 --> 00:52:01,480
RICHARD: Are there any cars
you're not going to destroy?

985
00:52:01,520 --> 00:52:03,160
How many cars
have you destroyed today?

986
00:52:03,200 --> 00:52:06,160
I didn't destroy it.
I'd stopped, as you saw.

987
00:52:06,200 --> 00:52:09,480
I saw you driving
like an absolute maniac...

988
00:52:09,520 --> 00:52:13,040
- Shut up!
- ...into this poor
man's classic Dacia.

989
00:52:13,080 --> 00:52:15,760
Anyway, James,
as you know, on  Top Gear...

990
00:52:15,800 --> 00:52:17,840
- Yes, goodbye.
- Thank you.

991
00:52:27,520 --> 00:52:31,320
JEREMY:
Our hunt for the fabled road
was not going well.

992
00:52:31,360 --> 00:52:33,000
And then it got worse.

993
00:52:35,400 --> 00:52:38,080
It went dark,
we couldn't find a hotel,

994
00:52:38,120 --> 00:52:41,800
the petrol stations were
closed, and because I was
very low on fuel,

995
00:52:41,840 --> 00:52:46,440
I found a quiet dead-end road
and suggested we
sleep in the cars.

996
00:52:46,480 --> 00:52:50,560
That put James and Richard
in a bit of a mood.

997
00:52:50,600 --> 00:52:52,760
Listen,
I can cheer you two up.

998
00:52:52,800 --> 00:52:54,720
Would you like some cannabis?

999
00:52:54,760 --> 00:52:56,240
- Yes, please.
- Right...

1000
00:52:58,480 --> 00:53:00,680
- Thanks.
- Eh?

1001
00:53:00,720 --> 00:53:06,320
That's cannabis. No,
specifically, it says it's
Swiss Cannabis Ice Tea.

1002
00:53:06,360 --> 00:53:09,080
- That's the best sort.
- You can get this
in petrol stations.

1003
00:53:09,120 --> 00:53:10,560
They sell cannabis
in petrol stations here?

1004
00:53:10,600 --> 00:53:15,160
Would you like some plum
liqueur in a bottle
the shape of a violin?

1005
00:53:15,200 --> 00:53:16,400
JAMES: Say yes.

1006
00:53:16,440 --> 00:53:17,960
Yes, it's just what
the doctor ordered.

1007
00:53:18,000 --> 00:53:19,680
[BOTTLE CLINKS]

1008
00:53:19,720 --> 00:53:23,400
- Oh, dear God!
- Gives you
a fantastic natural feeling.

1009
00:53:23,440 --> 00:53:25,000
Plum liqueur  andcannabis!

1010
00:53:28,040 --> 00:53:31,040
That's never
been tried before.
Give us a go. What's it like?

1011
00:53:31,080 --> 00:53:32,400
It's good.

1012
00:53:32,440 --> 00:53:34,960
- So we sleep in our cars...?
- Yes.

1013
00:53:35,000 --> 00:53:36,200
I haven't got a back seat.

1014
00:53:36,240 --> 00:53:38,920
I told you,
you brought the wrong car.

1015
00:53:38,960 --> 00:53:40,720
So, when I chose it,
I should've thought,

1016
00:53:40,760 --> 00:53:42,480
"Better get one
with a crap back seat."

1017
00:53:42,520 --> 00:53:45,600
- Just get in your car.
- [BOTTLE SMASHES]

1018
00:53:45,640 --> 00:53:48,520
Well,
that's the plum liqueur gone!

1019
00:53:48,560 --> 00:53:52,320
JEREMY:  We set about
our unplanned consumer test.

1020
00:53:52,360 --> 00:53:55,200
So, it is a four-seater,
they sell it as a four-seater.

1021
00:53:55,240 --> 00:53:58,480
That must mean
a human being can
get in the back.

1022
00:53:59,160 --> 00:54:00,360
Ah!

1023
00:54:00,400 --> 00:54:01,880
[HORN HONKS]

1024
00:54:03,520 --> 00:54:06,200
- [HORN BLARES]
- Sorry! Sorry, everyone.

1025
00:54:06,240 --> 00:54:07,880
- RICHARD: What are you doing?
- It's a design fault.

1026
00:54:07,920 --> 00:54:10,000
People are trying to sleep!

1027
00:54:13,280 --> 00:54:15,480
I'm gonna sleep in the front.

1028
00:54:28,360 --> 00:54:29,240
Ooh!

1029
00:54:29,920 --> 00:54:31,000
Ohh!

1030
00:54:32,080 --> 00:54:33,040
Ohhh!

1031
00:54:37,360 --> 00:54:38,560
[SIGHS]

1032
00:54:41,560 --> 00:54:42,960
Bloody hell!

1033
00:54:46,480 --> 00:54:47,880
- Oh!
- Oh, sorry, mate!

1034
00:54:47,920 --> 00:54:49,080
Ohh...

1035
00:54:50,240 --> 00:54:51,480
Did you sleep all right?

1036
00:54:51,520 --> 00:54:53,160
Yeah. Yeah, well.

1037
00:54:53,200 --> 00:54:54,480
Good.

1038
00:54:54,520 --> 00:54:57,040
- Did you not use the back?
- No, I tried...

1039
00:54:58,680 --> 00:55:00,080
It's cold.

1040
00:55:03,680 --> 00:55:05,000
What's that?

1041
00:55:14,120 --> 00:55:16,600
JEREMY: It's a dam.
But it's all right,
it's quite safe.

1042
00:55:16,640 --> 00:55:19,320
I should imagine it was built
by the Russians or
the North Koreans

1043
00:55:19,360 --> 00:55:20,760
so we'll be fine.

1044
00:55:20,800 --> 00:55:22,560
- Had I known...
- Sorry, mate.

1045
00:55:22,600 --> 00:55:26,000
...you'd parked us next
to that, I wouldn't have
enjoyed such deep sleep.

1046
00:55:26,040 --> 00:55:29,840
The quality of all Soviet
buildings is fantastic.
I'm sure that'll be...

1047
00:55:31,360 --> 00:55:33,000
Why don't you shut up?

1048
00:55:35,240 --> 00:55:38,120
JEREMY:  We set off once more
in search of our road.

1049
00:55:41,000 --> 00:55:42,560
Oh, my God!

1050
00:55:43,480 --> 00:55:45,960
JEREMY: Ohhhhhh, yes!

1051
00:55:46,760 --> 00:55:48,720
Suddenly, I'm awake.

1052
00:55:51,080 --> 00:55:54,120
And soon we
reach the mountains,
where the road surface

1053
00:55:54,160 --> 00:55:57,520
became as pimply
as a teenager's face.

1054
00:55:59,280 --> 00:56:01,960
Look at the road now!
It's practically ploughed!

1055
00:56:03,720 --> 00:56:07,160
JEREMY:
This was yet another problem
for James in his supercar.

1056
00:56:11,760 --> 00:56:13,800
Oh, please let it end!

1057
00:56:15,680 --> 00:56:18,000
The torture went on for hours,

1058
00:56:18,040 --> 00:56:21,960
but eventually,
the mountains
gave up their secret.

1059
00:56:22,520 --> 00:56:24,040
JEREMY: Look!

1060
00:56:24,080 --> 00:56:25,760
God!

1061
00:56:25,800 --> 00:56:29,240
[CHUCKLES] That's
the most amazing road
I've ever seen.

1062
00:56:32,680 --> 00:56:38,080
Built in the '70s,
this is
the Transfagarasan highway.

1063
00:56:38,120 --> 00:56:42,160
6,000 tonnes of dynamite
were used to make it

1064
00:56:42,200 --> 00:56:44,160
and 40 lives lost.

1065
00:56:48,560 --> 00:56:52,080
But from above,
it looks like
every great corner

1066
00:56:52,120 --> 00:56:54,640
from every great racetrack
in the world

1067
00:56:54,680 --> 00:56:56,120
has been knitted together

1068
00:56:56,160 --> 00:56:58,960
to create one
unbroken grey ribbon

1069
00:56:59,000 --> 00:57:01,560
of automotive perfection.

1070
00:57:05,600 --> 00:57:09,000
[ENGINES ROAR]

1071
00:57:20,680 --> 00:57:24,760
This is what we came here for!
Oh, yes!

1072
00:57:24,800 --> 00:57:29,480
Our cars had done motorways
and city centres
and Gypsy villages,

1073
00:57:29,520 --> 00:57:31,760
they'd been slept
in and written on,

1074
00:57:31,800 --> 00:57:36,000
but now they had a chance
to let their hair down.

1075
00:57:49,400 --> 00:57:51,360
Oh, that's heavenly.

1076
00:57:51,400 --> 00:57:54,480
That traction control now
in a setting that allows
a little bit of slip.

1077
00:58:04,320 --> 00:58:06,160
Look at that!

1078
00:58:06,200 --> 00:58:10,040
The grip! The balance!
God, they've worked on this.

1079
00:58:12,360 --> 00:58:17,640
RICHARD:  But here on
this road, the happiest bunny
of us all was James.

1080
00:58:21,720 --> 00:58:24,080
I brought the right car!

1081
00:58:27,400 --> 00:58:29,480
Lamborghini payback time!

1082
00:58:30,960 --> 00:58:32,040
Oh, yeah!

1083
00:58:38,080 --> 00:58:42,600
I have to say, this is one of
the two or three best cars in
the world right now.

1084
00:58:46,880 --> 00:58:51,000
And the strange
thing is, those two
are driving two of the others.

1085
00:58:52,520 --> 00:58:56,280
The road just got
better and better.

1086
00:58:56,320 --> 00:58:57,720
We were wrong!

1087
00:58:57,760 --> 00:58:59,760
This is better
than the Stelvio.

1088
00:58:59,800 --> 00:59:03,360
This is the best
road in the world!

1089
00:59:03,400 --> 00:59:06,960
And the Romanian
helicopter cameraman
wasn't bad, either.

1090
00:59:08,480 --> 00:59:10,680
[ENGINES ROAR]

1091
00:59:13,160 --> 00:59:14,560
[CHUCKLING]

1092
00:59:15,680 --> 00:59:19,560
What a finale to
our Grand Tour!

1093
00:59:19,600 --> 00:59:22,680
Just wanna say, Romania,
thank you for having us,

1094
00:59:22,720 --> 00:59:25,880
and can we stay...forever?

1095
00:59:39,200 --> 00:59:41,320
[CHEERING AND APPLAUSE]

1096
00:59:41,360 --> 00:59:43,160
[APPLAUSE DROWNS SPEECH]

1097
00:59:47,320 --> 00:59:49,160
Anyway...

1098
00:59:49,200 --> 00:59:51,480
what we learned from
our lengthy trip to Romania

1099
00:59:51,520 --> 00:59:54,400
was that the Aston Martin,
as I predicted
at the beginning,

1100
00:59:54,440 --> 00:59:55,840
was the best.

1101
00:59:55,880 --> 00:59:57,280
Except it was the Lamborghini.

1102
00:59:57,320 --> 00:59:59,120
No, the Ferrari was the best.

1103
00:59:59,160 --> 01:00:04,280
Look, guys,
the two people whose opinion
I respect most of all

1104
01:00:04,320 --> 01:00:06,120
on all matters motoring -

1105
01:00:06,160 --> 01:00:10,600
The Stig and Tiff Needell -
both say that the Aston Martin

1106
01:00:10,640 --> 01:00:12,720
is the best car in
the world right now.

1107
01:00:12,760 --> 01:00:14,080
Well, they're both wrong.

1108
01:00:14,120 --> 01:00:16,560
Aha!
Let me draw your attention
to this.

1109
01:00:16,600 --> 01:00:20,600
This is a report of our visit
in one of the leading
Romanian newspapers,

1110
01:00:20,640 --> 01:00:23,520
and look at
the caption to this picture
here. It's in Romanian,

1111
01:00:23,560 --> 01:00:26,280
but I'll translate.
"Jeremy Clarkson
in the Aston Martin,

1112
01:00:26,320 --> 01:00:29,160
"the best car in the world,
camera video."

1113
01:00:30,360 --> 01:00:31,440
It doesn't say that.

1114
01:00:31,480 --> 01:00:32,880
Yes, it does.

1115
01:00:32,920 --> 01:00:34,400
And on that bombshell,
it is time to end.

1116
01:00:34,440 --> 01:00:36,640
Thank you so
much for watching.
Good night!

1117
01:00:36,680 --> 01:00:38,760
[CHEERING AND APPLAUSE]

